<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France "Worried and Shocked" by Wave of Violences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is
worried and shocked by the escalating violences in Algeria, which
killed at least 150 people since the beginning of the Muslim
festival of Ramadan on January 10.
</P>
<P>
"In these tragic and revolting circumstances, we naturally have
to express our sadness and sympathy (with the Algerian people),"
said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
A car bomb attack killed at least 21 people on a street in the
Algerian capital Algiers Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic extremists of the Armed Islamic Group have vowed to
escalate the war and denied neutrality of civilians.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried and shocked by the wave of violences which hit
blindly and savagely the Algerian people, especially those of the
capital (Algiers), whose population has been toughly tested," said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that France, the former colonial power of Algeria and the
biggest economic and financial partner of the country, condemns the
violence, "no matter where it comes from, what it is, and what its
motives are." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
