<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazarbayev Calls for Fundamental Reform of CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev has called for fundamental reform of the Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS), saying that without change, it will
become irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Kazakhstan Pravda, Nazarbayev said that
since it was set up at the end of 1991, the CIS had failed to
unite the republics of the former Soviet Union. Instead these
countries had gradually become alienated from each other
politically, economically and socially, Nazarbayev said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the life of the CIS could be divided into two
stages: the first from 1991-1992, and the second from 1993 onwards.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, the economic system still in place after
the collapse of the Soviet Union still functioned. But in the
second stage, economic growth in all CIS member states dropped
significantly, damaging the economic ties linking the countries.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said 1997 would be crucial to CIS's future. Member
states must establish relations of mutual respect, clear up their
mistrust of each other, and promote economic integration.
</P>
<P>
But the president was upbeat on some aspects of the CIS and
said the organization had made some achievements.
</P>
<P>
"At least, we have successfully avoided such bloody clashes as
those that happened in the former Yugoslavia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
