<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-21 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reiterates Readiness to Resume Talks With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel reiterated today its
readiness to resume peace talks with Syria, which have been
stalled for months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a tour to the police headquarters today,
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu said that Israel was
interested in restarting the peace negotiations with Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said there were indications that the United States
would make new efforts to start the Israeli-Syrian talks
since the Monday inauguration of President Bill Clinton for a
second term.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also stressed
that Israel was ready to restart negotiations with Syria at
any time in any place.
</P>
<P>
The minister was making the comments during a meeting with
U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk and other diplomats, who
said the recent Hebron agreement had created favorable atmosphere
for pushing forward the whole Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel's call for renewing peace talks came after it completed
the long-delayed Hebron redeployment last Friday, a move regarded
as a major step to ease regional tension and push forward the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Egypt are moving quickly to make new efforts
to help resume the Israeli-Syrian talks that have been
suspended since early last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel is demanding renewing talks without any prior
conditions, while at the same time vows never to relinquish its
self-claimed sovereignty over the Golan Heights, which it seized
from Syria in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Syria has declared that the only way to resume
peace talks was Israel's total withdrawal from the Golan
Heights. It urged Israel to restart the talks from where they were
left off last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel's previous Labor government reportedly had committed
itself to withdrawal from the Golan Heights in order to seal a
peace pact with Damascus, but the current Likud government has
refused to recognize this as the basis for renewing
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
