<HEADLINE> Tensions Ease After Hebron Redeployment: Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A top Israeli army
officer said today that tensions have eased in the West Bank
since the Israeli army concluded its troops' redeployment in
Hebron, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Appearing in the Foreign Affair and Defense Committee of
the Knesset (Israel's parliament), Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, chief of
staff of the Israeli army, said that "most people are much
relaxed now."
</P>
<P>
Before the Hebron pullback, there had been reports from
diplomatic and security establishments of tensions in the West
Bank, particularly in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
However, Shahak warned that there is still a small number
of people who could cause trouble, adding that both the Israelis
and Palestinians must act against them.
</P>
<P>
The chief of staff also expressed his hope that the
Palestinian police and the Palestinian National Authority "will
implement their responsibility," while on the other hand, the
Israeli side will try its best.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Israeli army completed its long-awaited
redeployment in the West Bank town of Hebron, less than
eight hours after the Knesset approved the Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
forces in the West Bank and a Hebron native, said that the
Palestinians would try to fulfill their commitments in
the Hebron accord, and he hoped that the Israelis would do
the same.
</P>
<P>
As Palestinian policemen now taking over observation positions
close to the Jewish neighborhood, the residents in Hebron,
Jews and Palestinians, are entering a new era, in which they
will live side-by-side, hopefully in a peaceful way.
</P>
</TEXT>
