<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Misguidance in Vain  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- China's state news agency,
Xinhua, released an article, entitled "Misguidance In Vain",
written by Wen Ming, today.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that recently some US news media have
published commentaries and reports that are obviously against the
wishes of the people of both China and the United States, and in a
sharp contrast to the two countries' improved relations.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that there are a number of columnists and
scholars in the US who have a deeply-rooted prejudice and
hostility toward China, which perseveres in the road of socialism,
and are extremely reluctant to resign themselves to the fact that
the "overall containment" policy used against China has ended in
failure.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, they have tried every means to undermine China's
image worldwide by misleading the general public in the US,
exerting influence on decision-makers, and throwing up barriers to
Sino-US relations by means of the news media," it said.
</P>
<P>
While continuing with different versions of the "China Threat",
these people rack their brains to come up with new Anti-China
theories. "Sometimes they spread pessimism and skepticism about
the return and future of Hong Kong, urging the US government to
step forward to interfere in an attempt to protect the 'freedom'
of Hong Kong. At other times they framed up lies about Tibet,
claiming that the people of the ethnic Tibetan group are still
being 'persecuted'," it noted.
</P>
<P>
These people deliberately turn a blind eye to China's political
stability and booming economy, and view the country with sarcasm
and in a distorted way.
</P>
<P>
They also wilfully accuse the Chinese government of "playing
the nationalism card", and openly call for Americans to boycott
Chinese goods.
</P>
<P>
"It's easy to change rivers and mountains but hard to change a
person's nature," as a Chinese proverb goes. Since they think they
are the chosen people and have the right to tell anybody what to
do, the article said, it's not easy to expect them to abandon
their hostility to China. It is necessary, however, to refute
these fallacies to allow for a correct view of the facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
