<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Backs Cape Town's Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Council of
Sport in Africa (SCSA) has endorsed South Africa's bid to host
the 2004 Olympic Games in Cape Town as "an African bid", the
South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Cape Town, Chief Executive
Officer of the Cape Town Olympic bid committee, Chris Ball, said
the SCSA had requested the continent's ministers of youth and
sport to actively support South Africa's bidding efforts.
</P>
<P>
Ball said SCSA's support was of special significance because
President Nelson Mandela and all levels of the South African
government had already stated that Cape Town's bid was as much
Africa's as it is South Africa's.
</P>
<P>
"The SCSA's pledge of support strongly reinforces our efforts
to bring the Olympic games to Africa for the first time," said
Ball.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town is the only African city among the 11 cities of the
world bidding for the right to host the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee is expected to announce a
shortlist of the four or five finalist bidding cities on March 7,
and the 2004 host city will be named on September 5.
</P>
<P>
The other bidding cities are Athens, Buenos Aires, Istanbul,
Lille, Rio de Janeiro, Rome, San Juan, Seville, Stockholm and St.
Petersburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
