<HEADLINE> Misguidance in Vain (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some US newspapers, the article noted, have tried to deprive
China of its right to self-defense and explanation, and have
hurled unfounded charges against China and interfered with its
internal affairs themselves.
</P>
<P>
They have imposed recrimination upon China when it tries to
speak for itself, and gone so far to curse the Chinese government
as peddling "nationalism and exclusivism" as Hitler and his like
did, and they even voiced their resentment to the indignation of
the Chinese people about Japanese rightists' attempts to revive
militarism.
</P>
<P>
"What these people have is nothing but a psychology typical of
hegemonists," the article notes.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, it goes on to say, China is striving to
promote among its people a kind of patriotism with reasoning. "The
Chinese do not go in for expansionism, nor will they tolerate
being suppressed or humiliated by anyone."
</P>
<P>
It points out that China's stability and development are an
indispensable, important factor to world peace, stability, and
development, and that China is seeking prosperity so as to make
more contributions to world peace.
</P>
<P>
"Some American politicians and members of the news media
deliberately confuse the lofty patriotic ideals of the Chinese
people with the narrow concept of nationalism and use this to
confuse the general public and place yet another obstacle in the
way of improved Sino-US relations," it said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that stable relations between China and the US comply
with the trend in the world development, and are in the interests
of both countries. With increased exchanges between the two
countries, more Americans have become aware that many reports in
the US media are simply not true, and say that they do not want
to be misguided any more.
</P>
<P>
"The cost of fooling the people will be the loss of their faith
and trust, and anyone trapped in Cold War thinking who refuses to
face reality will be surely abandoned by the people - this is a
historical law," it concludes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Misguidance in Vain  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The commentator's article cited a recent article from
"U.S.A. Today" that described China as a future "superpower" that
the US must take precautions against.
</P>
<P>
After China has taken back Hong Kong, Macao, and eventually
Taiwan, the American article claimed, the country will become
powerful enough to trigger a new round of Cold War and arms race.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone with an understanding of China can clearly see that
these words are just sheer nonsense," the article went on to say,
adding that the Chinese government has always followed an
independent foreign policy of peace, and is in firm opposition to
any form of hegemonism and power politics.
</P>
<P>
It said that 22 years ago, Senior Leader Deng Xiaoping had
already made the solemn declaration at the Six Special Meeting of
the United Nations General Assembly that China would never be a
superpower. "China is no threat to other countries now, and it
will not pose any threat to other nations even when it is even
more developed and its comprehensive national strength is
strengthened," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Some people in the West hold a very strange logic. Based on the
history of the US, Britain and other Western nations growing in
strength, from weak to strong, and finally launching aggression
against other countries, they alleged that China, too, will take
the similar road. The basic reason for some Americans feeling
nervous about China's growth is the fact that China's development
has added strength to the force of peace in the world, which
certainly is definitely no good news for the hegemonists.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that, while some Americans claim to be greatly
concerned about security in the Pacific region, they never utter a
word against Japan, which is rapidly becoming a military power
with a defense budget of over 50 billion US dollars a year, the
world's second largest. It goes on to note, "Quite to the
contrary, the US has even strengthened its security pact with
Japan, and extended its scope of defense to cover the whole
Asia-Pacific region that includes China."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China's military budget is less than one tenth that
of the US, which has become a major source of global disturbance
with a continuous display of military might.
</P>
<P>
"These facts can only lead us to conclude that the
so-called 'China Threat' is merely a pretext resorted to limit
China's development, one that has been refuted not only by Third
World countries, but also by a lot of sensible and far-sighted
people inside the US," it said.
</P>
<P>
It also quoted former President George Bush as saying that he
never regarded China as a threat, and that China should deserve
due respect as a proud country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
