<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC,FAO Agricultural Workshop Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A three-day agricultural
workshop organized by the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) and the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organisation
(FAO) opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 participants from 11 of the 12 SADC countries will
discuss agricultural policies of the SADC member countries, the
impact of the trade agreements on food security and the
implications for agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
FAO's eastern and southern Africa regional representative,
Victoria Sekitoleko, told the meeting that SADC countries should
change their agricultural policies to take into account economic
reforms currently underway.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the way agriculture is undertaken will
change radically in the future, hence the need for new policies.
</P>
<P>
"First and foremost, this concerns the list of policies that
are discouraged and those that are acceptable. Overall trade
regimes in future should be much more transparent and, as a
result, the quality of price signals faced by producers and
consumers should improve," said Sekitoleko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
