<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Inflation Falls to 39 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Annual inflation slowed
significantly in Ukraine last year, rising 39 percent compared
with more than 1,000 percent in 1993, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Valery Litvitsky, chief economic advisor to Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma, said the fall in production had also slowed down,
from 15 percent in 1995 to 5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"It's a sign of the beginning of stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Litvitsky warned that the potential for inflation still
exists in the government's immense debts to workers in the form of
some 1 billion hryvnas (530 million U.S. dollars) in unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
Disgruntled mine workers protested outside government
headquarters last week to demand up to 12 months of back pay.
</P>
<P>
Litvitsky said the country needed to keep a tight rein on
inflation to secure more financial assistance from international
lenders. The nation has absorbed only 1 billion dollars of foreign
investment since independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Economic reform in Ukraine has been slower than in many other
former Soviet republics. The underground economy remains huge and
analysts believe up to 45 percent of Ukrainians live below the
poverty line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
