<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Top Diplomat to Meet NATO Chief Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, who met in
Moscow on Monday, will hold another round of talks next month, a
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Tarasov, director of the ministry's press and
information department, did not specify the date or venue of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the first round of talks between the two men
was "useful," although "the sides differ in their approaches to a
number of issues."
</P>
<P>
Solana arrived in Moscow on Sunday evening and held his first
round of talks with Primakov on Monday over NATO's eastward
expansion plans, which Russia strongly opposes.
</P>
<P>
The two sides failed to reach agreement on the issue but, said
Tarasov, no one should have expected any sensational breakthrough
from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said Primakov told Solana negotiations on Russian relations
with NATO and the relationship itself could not be viewed as
"compensation" for Russian agreement on NATO's plans to admit
former Warsaw Pact countries. He said Moscow would remain negative
about NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said that this stance is dictated by a whole range of
political, military-strategic and moral-psychological reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of any statements and intentions, any unbiased
observer can clearly see that expansion of the alliance creates
the threat of new division lines in Europe, which could lead to
consequences all of us tried to get rid of with the end of the
Cold war," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, he said, ways needed to be found to avoid any
eastward spread of NATO military infrastructure and the 1991
Conventional Forces in Europe Treaty signed before the fall of the
Soviet Union needed to be changed to take account of the new
geopolitical realities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The talks would also try to work out a formula for Moscow-NATO
relations, which would meet Russia's security requirements and the
tasks of building a new Europe in the 21st century, Tarasov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
