<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Praise Rule of Returned Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 21 (Xinhua) -- China's 18-year's of sending
scholars abroad for further study has trained a large group of
professionals and enlarged China's cooperation with other
countries in science and technology, education, culture, economy
and trade, according to Wei Yu, vice-minister of the State
Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
Wei was speaking today at a national conference on overseas
scholars held by the SEC and the Ministry of Personnel, the first
of its kind ever held in China since the late 1970s when the
country started its reform and opening up drive.
</P>
<P>
Wei, got a doctorate in electronics from Aachen Industrial
University in Germany, in 1981, and was the first women from new
China to get a doctorate from that university.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 157 academics of the Chinese Academy
of Engineering (CAE) were scholars who returned to China over the
past decade or so. Returned scholars also account for over half of
those doing key scientific research projects or who are listed as
top professionals given priority in research fund.
</P>
<P>
To help overseas scholars work for the country, various
organizations were formed, including the Chinese Service Center
for Scholarly Exchange. Education sections were also set up in
Chinese embassies or consulates in foreign countries where most
overseas scholars stay and study.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Service Center for Scholarly Exchange has 23
branches in China and service centers in Berlin, San Francisco,
and New York so that it can provide direct services overseas.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, approximately 270,000 Chinese went
abroad for advanced training over the past 18 years. Over 120,000
of them were sponsored by the State or their work units, with the
remainder self-supporting.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 of these people have completed their overseas study
and returned.
</P>
<P>
However, Wei added, most of these scholars chose to work in
educational or scientific research institutes based in Beijing or
other big or medium-sized coastal cities, which are more developed
than other parts of the country, and not enough returning scholars
want to work in central or western areas.
</P>
<P>
Wei expressed the hope that departments and officials would
work harder to provide still better working and living conditions
for returning scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
