<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Leaves for Prague to Sign Czech-German Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
leaves for Prague today to sign a highly controversial
Czech-German reconciliation accord.
</P>
<P>
The accord, to be signed by Kohl and Czech Prime Minister
Vaclav Klaus at 4:15 p.m.(1515 GMT), is the result of more than
two years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The deal is aimed at helping heal the wounds of World War Two
and its aftermath. It also includes German support for Czech
membership of the European Union and North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Bonn expresses sorrow for the 1938-45 Nazi
occupation of Czech land. Prague also states its regret for Czech
brutality in the post-war expulsion of Sudeten Germans.
</P>
<P>
Czech President Vaclav Havel said that the declaration between
the two nations is a "great step forward" and will undoubtedly
help people reconsider the past, though it cannot thoroughly
change the biased attitudes the two countries have held
towards each other.
</P>
<P>
Havel's comments were echoed in the positive response from
different political parties in Germany. The Chairman of the Free
Democratic Party Wolfgang Gerhardt hailed the accord as "one
shaping a common future for wronged Germans and Czechs".
</P>
<P>
Ex-Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said it opens a road
leading to the future of Europe for both countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Sudeten Germans held a protest rally against the
declaration, saying it has not solved any controversial problems
left behind by history, but merely creates more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
