<HEADLINE> Global Musical Sales to Rise 7 Percent Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The world's musical sales are
expected to increase 7 percent each year between 1997 and 2002
with retail sales hitting 62.12 billion U.S. dollars in 2002,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The study, to be published later this week by Market Tracking
International (MTI), suggested that the global musical market
should regain momentum in the coming years following a slowdown in
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
The global music market grew by 66 percent from 1990 to 38.8
billion dollars in 1995, but MTI estimates it increased just 5
percent last year to 40.86 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the estimated sales will increase 7 percent this year
to amount to 43.87 billion dollars with Asia's sales trebling to
8.82 billion dollars by 2002, the fastest growing rate.
</P>
<P>
Musical sales are also expected to treble to 1.83 billion
dollars in eastern Europe during the period, and Latin America
market will rise 139 percent in the same period to 4.46 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
