<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on European Arms Treaty Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The conference to revise the
Treaty on Conventional Armed Forces in Europe opens here today in
a bid to decide future ceiling numbers on troops, tanks, fighters
and artillery in European countries.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by 30 member states of NATO and the
former Warsaw Pact, will focus on amendments to the treaty signed
by NATO and Warsaw Pact member countries in 1990 before the fall
of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Amendments to the treaty are being demanded by Russia to take
account of the significant changes which have taken place in the
continent's political landscape since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, negotiated under the auspices of the Organization
of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), was signed by the
member states of NATO and of the now defunct Warsaw Pact to cap
the levels of weapons and troops around Europe. It took effect on
November 17 1995.
</P>
<P>
But just before that date, Russia announced that its could not
meet its treaty obligations because it feared that reduced
military might on its frontiers would ruin its defense
capabilities. It was particularly concerned about its southern
flank near the troubled Caucasus, where Russia troops once fought
Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
By missing the deadline Russia was in technical violation of
the pact, but it argued that the treaty limits on military
equipment allowed on a state's borders had to be altered, because
Russia's frontiers were not the same as the Soviet Union's.
</P>
<P>
The United States accepted Moscow's argument and put pressure
on its NATO allies to agree to adapt the pact, despite concern
from Norway and Turkey over any increase in Russian military
equipment near their border.
</P>
<P>
The conference, decided by the OSCE summit last December, is
expected to last one and half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
