<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Needs Radical Policy Initiatives: Business Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain's business needs a
number of radical policy initiatives by the next government if the
UK is to climb the prosperity league table, senior business
leaders argue.
</P>
<P>
A report, entitled, Promoting Prosperity: A Business Agenda for
Britain, launched here today analyses why the UK is not performing
better, sets out what principles should guide future business
policy and establishes an agenda for action for the next
government.
</P>
<P>
The report was unanimously adopted by the Commission on Public
Policy and British Business (CPPBB) which includes senior business
leaders in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Promoting Prosperity identifies four linked problems: too many
unsuccessful companies, too many underachieving people, too little
investment, and too frequent shifts in government policy.
</P>
<P>
These problems would be remedied if the government were to:
promote competition and cooperation, foster far-sighted companies,
mobilize people's potential, and maintain greater consistency in
its policies, the report adds.
</P>
<P>
Among a large range of recommendations, Promoting Prosperity
calls for: -- Stiffer competition policy,
</P>
<P>
-- A new Council of Institutional Investors to target
underperforming companies,
</P>
<P>
-- Increased funding for nursery and primary education,
</P>
<P>
-- A Level reform to reduce the damaging effects of early
specialization by children.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the above measures, it also calls for: Independence
for the Bank of England to help steady the roller-coaster
macro-economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition the Commission accepts the need for a national
minimum wage to control welfare costs and favors opting-in to the
Social Chapter.
</P>
<P>
But it is relatively cautious on EMU entry which it views as
politically desirable to retain influence in the Single Market but
whose economic advantages are less clear.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Promoting Prosperity, Opposition Leader Tony
Blair said: "This report sets the business policy agenda for the
next decade."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the conclusion of the report that UK's economy is
in the position of "relative decline", Michael Heseltine, Deputy
Prime Minister, said: "Britain's relative decline has been
reversed for the first time since the Second World War."
</P>
<P>
He also quoted the latest OECD Economic Outlook as saying
"Britain's prospects for achieving sustained output growth and low
inflation are the best in 30 years."
</P>
<P>
"The Commission can't bring itself to get the story right,"
said, the Deputy Prime Minister. "The relative decline", they
concluded "may be bottoming out", he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
