<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-21 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects US Proposal on Banning Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government told
the United States and the European Union today that it would not
bow to a U.S.-backed proposal on banning overflights of Greek and
Turkish military aircraft in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides said that such a move
would be tantamount to conceding the right to control its air
space to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He announced the Cypriot position during his meetings with the
U.S. ambassador here and the ambassadors of EU members.
</P>
<P>
"A halt of overflights would mean that we recognize the right
to Turkey to share with us ownership of our air space. This
cannot be accepted," Michaelides told reporters after the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Cypriot government has given assurances to ban
overflights when the peace talks start, the minister said the
government will refrain from any move that would create
tension.
</P>
<P>
"We may take certain steps unilaterally to facilitate the
climate of the dialogue without asking anything in return from
the other side," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill expressed
disappointment today with the Cypriot government's decision,
backed by Athens, not to accept the U.S. proposal for a
moratorium on overflights of Greek and Turkish military aircraft
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed that this opportunity to move forward
was not taken," Brill said after his meeting with Michaelides.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. position, Michaelides said "the
U.S. may be disappointed because they wished to see each step
adopted as proposed. We have heard this but we have also
explained that any moves taken must not have a poltical cost."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. disappointment may have negative
repercussions on the U.S. initiative on Cyprus, which is
expected to be launched in April, the minister said "I do not
think so because the U.S. recognizes that Turkey poses the main
problem, there are far more flights by Turkish aircraft than
Greek planes."
</P>
<P>
He said he explained to the ambassadors that "Cyprus wishes
to see intensive effort to prepare the ground before direct
negotiations begin."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal for a ban on military flights over the
island was first put forward last summer by Madeleine Albright,
former U.S. permanent representative to the United Nations and
now new U.S. secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Carey Cavanaugh reiterated the proposal
during his recent three-nation tour which took him to Cyprus,
Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
But Cyprus' President Glafcos Clerides announced after his
talks with Greek leaders during his recent visit to Greece that
the moratorium banning Greek and Turkish military aircraft
flights over the island "is dead."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Greece of rejecting the U.S. proposal,
saying that the Greek government was reluctant to ease tensions
on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The relation between Greece and Turkey has always been tense
for the Aegean and Cyprus issues, and has become even worse as a
result of the Cypriot government's decision to buy Russian-made
S-300 missiles with a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive coup by supporters of union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Governor Repeats Call for Interest Rate Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the Bank of
England Eddie George Monday night delivered an unequivocal warning
that interest rates would have to rise if inflation was to be kept
in check.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to bankers in Edinburgh, Scotland, the governor
renewed his call for "a modest pre-emptive tightening of monetary
policy" to prevent a resurgence in inflation.
</P>
<P>
His call came less than a week after his monthly monetary
meeting with the Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke at
which Clarke decided to leave interest rates unchanged from the
current six percent.
</P>
<P>
Clarke had cited the strength of sterling as the key reason he
did not raise rates, saying that "the big thing at the moment is
that the pound is very strong and that is very anti-inflationary".
</P>
<P>
However, the governor indicated that the pound should not be
used as an excuse to delay raising rates, as the stronger exchange
rate had no direct effect on the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
"There could be real dangers in allowing justified concern
about the exchange rate to deflect us too long from moving
gradually to moderate the (economic) upswing," George added.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor reiterated the Bank of England's
belief that the earlier rates were increased, the less they would
ultimately have to rise.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that rapid falls in unemployment and the
recovery in the housing market indicated demand might be
strengthening and said that was why he believed that the choice of
a rise of interest rates was not whether or not, it is sooner or
later, less or more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Threats to S. Africa Over Arms Sales, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) --The United States
Ambassador to South Africa James Joseph said on Tuesday his
country was not threatening Pretoria over a possible 638 million
U.S. Dollar arms deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
" No one in the U.S. administration is threatening South
Africa," Joseph told reporters in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Referring to remarks by a U.S. State Department Spokesman one
week ago that the U.S. might to suspend aid to South Africa if
the latter sells advanced arms to Syria, Joseph said what the
U.S.government spokesman said meant that Washington is required
to implement state laws. Such acknowlegement should not be
considered a threat, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. counter-terrorism act requires the American
government to act against countries which provide lethal military
equipemnt to "state sponsors of terrorism".
</P>
<P>
Joseph said: " It is no secret that like any two friends, we
have occasional areas of disagreement...we respect South Africa's
policy of universality and its right to choose its own friends
based on its priorities."
</P>
<P>
On relations between Washingtong and Pretoria, Josheph said
the U.S. had a five billion dollar trade relationship with South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Since the elections in 1994, American firms have been
investing in South Africa at a rate of almost double that of all
other countries combine.
</P>
<P>
" Over the last year alone, American companies have been
entering or expanding their operations in South Africa at the
rate of one per week," the U.S. ambassador said. " There are now
more than 700 American companies engaged in some form of business
activity in South Africa. They have sales of almost eight billion
U.S. Dollars and assets of more than 10 billion U.S. Dollars," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Joseph said jobs created by U.S. investment increased by 29
percent in South Africa last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.is also the largest donor country in South Africa with
more than 2.5 billion Rand (538 million U.S.Dollars)provided over
a three year period for the development of the new South Africa,
Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
Private U.S. foundations also contributed almost 200 million
Rand (43 million U.S.Dollars) annually to South Africa, the U.S.
ambassador said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
