<HEADLINE> SADC Parliamentary Forum to Be Held in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from the 12
member states of the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC)
will start their two-day parliamentary forum annual meeting in
Tanzania's capital of Dar es Salaam on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be opened by Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa, in the city, would be held following the executive
committee meeting which would receive, consider and approve the
annual budget and activities for the forum for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The plenary meeting is also expected to ratify the SADC
parliamentary forum's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The forum is aimed at promoting regional peace, security and
stability on collective responsibility basis and supporting the
development of permanent conflict resolution mechanism in the SADC
sub-region, strengthening solidarity and building a sense of
common destiny among the people of the area.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives of the forum include popularizing the concept
of development and co-operation within the region, increasing
economical and political prosperity, and ensuring effective
implementation of democratic principals.
</P>
<P>
SADC groups Tanzania, Zambia, Malawi, Mozambique, Zimbabwe,
Botswana, Angola, Namibia, South Africa, Lesotho, Swaziland and
Mauritius. 
</P>
