<HEADLINE> Cyprus Dismisses Turkish Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today turned down the
Turkish threats that it will set up air and naval bases in
northern part of the island and dismissed them as "not serious."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a joint declaration issued Monday in Ankara
after a meeting between Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, Cypriot Foreign Minister
Alecos Michaelides said the occupied part of the island is in
itself a Turkish military base and therefore the Cypriot
government does not consider Ankara's threats as serious.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, Turkey has threatened to set up air
and naval bases in the Turkish-occupied areas of the island if
the Cypriot government deploys Russian-made anti-aircraft
missiles on the island and goes ahead with establishing an
air and naval base.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that any aggression directed against
Turkey or the Turkish Cypriot regime in northern Cyprus "will be
jointly confronted and the military planning and co-ordination
necessary for this will be done."
</P>
<P>
Michaelides said that for the past 22 years Turkey has been
occupying 37 per cent of the island's territory, adding that
Turkey keeps 35,000 troops on the island and uses the airport at
Lefkoniko for military purposes and Kyrenia as a naval base.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The tension has escalated on the island following the Cypriot
government's recent decision to buy Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missiles with a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
