<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Conference on Disarmament Begins Without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference on
Disarmament (CD) began its 1997 session with no agreed agenda here
today.
</P>
<P>
"The CD is supposed to adopt the agenda and its work program at
the beginning of the session. But unfortunately I have to inform
you that the consultation is still under way," South Korean
Ambassador Joun Yung Sun told reporters at the end of today's
session.
</P>
<P>
Sun said, "I hope, in the very near future, we'll be able to
get together and discuss the possibility of the adoption of the
agenda." Items in his draft agenda include nuclear disarmament,
cut-off treaty, negative security assurances, transparency in
armaments, prevention of an arms race in outer space and
anti-personnel land-mines, and regional disarmament.
</P>
<P>
During the current session from January 21 to March 27,
delegates from 61 CD members will discuss proposed issues and then
adopt an agenda if consensus could be reached after consultations.
</P>
<P>
After two-and-a-half years of negotiations culminating in the
drafting of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treat approved by
the UN General Assembly last September, the CD is now ready to
focus increased attention on other issues on the international
disarmament agenda.
</P>
<P>
The question of nuclear disarmament is at the heart of the
concerns of many delegations, with 21 non-aligned nations calling
for the establishment of an ad hoc committee on nuclear
disarmament as a matter of priority on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, like Italy and the United States, insist
that a ban of the production of weapons-grade fissile material and
a solution of the problem of anti-personnel land-mines should be
considered in the CD session. "These are the two main subjects we
have identified," said Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs at a
separate press conference.
</P>
<P>
The CD presidency rotates among all of its members for a four
working-week period in accordance with the listing of the
membership in English alphabetical order. The representatives of
the following member states will serve as conference presidents
during the 1997 session: South Korea, Romania, Russia, Senegal,
Slovakia, and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
