<HEADLINE> Airbus to Go Ahead with "Super Airliner" Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Airbus Industry, the European
aircraft manufacturer, announced today that it would press ahead
with its plans to build a "super airliner", according to a BBC
television report.
</P>
<P>
The four-nation European consortium reaffirmed its
determination to stick to its super jet project following the
decision by its main U.S. rival Boeing to drop its plans for its
990-seater airliner.
</P>
<P>
Boeing was reported as saying that it was too risky to spend 5
billion pounds (about 8 billion U.S. dollars) on large aircraft
when there were few orders for them.
</P>
<P>
However, Airbus Industry, in which British Aerospace has a 20
percent stake, insisted that there was a demand for a "superliner"
in the world aviation market.
</P>
<P>
Boeing and Airbus are the two largest players in the global
aircraft manufacturing field and Airbus is now under great
pressure to promote its competition capabilities following
Boeing's successful merging of MacDonald, another major U.S.
aircraft manufacturer. 
</P>
