<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stiffer Competition Policy Central to Strengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Commission on Public Policy
and British Business's (CPPBB) report launched here today, argues
that the current government has failed British business by
dragging its feet on promised reforms of UK competition policy.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled Promoting Prosperity describes current
policy as "feeble" since although anti-competitive practices may
be banned, there is little other penalty on offending companies.
</P>
<P>
It recommends that the next government take specific steps to
stiffen competition policy and that it should also investigate
other ways of raising the quality of domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The report calls for the overall design of competition policy
to be shifted more towards the prohibition approach with legal
penalties and fines for specified anti-competitive practices.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report argues that the institutions of
competition policy require an overhaul to make policy more
effective and less prone to political interference.
</P>
<P>
Promoting Prosperity details following policy changes to
promote competitive product markets:
</P>
<P>
-- The government should adopt a prohibition approach to
restrictive agreements and abuse of market power with stiffer
penalties for anti-competitive behavior,
</P>
<P>
-- There should be a substantial increase in the powers of the
Director General of Fair Trading to investigate suspected
anti-competitive behavior,
</P>
<P>
-- The Secretary of State's role in competition policy should
be made transparent through the obligatory publication of a report
with reasons for his or her decisions,
</P>
<P>
-- The responsibilities of the Office of Fair Trading and the
Commission of Monopoly and Mergence should be realigned to make
the OFT the principal agent of investigation and prosecution with
the MMC concentrating on adjudication,
</P>
<P>
-- The government should be predisposed to public disclosure of
the information it has about companies where that would enable
consumers to make more informed choices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
