<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu is about
to invite some of the world's top businessmen, led by
U.S. software giant Bill Gates, to visit Israel in a bid to
attract more foreign investment, Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The list of guests also includes other big names such as Wall
Street financier George Soros, Japan's Itocho Corp. President
Minoru Murofushi, Wolkswagen Chief Executive (CEO) Ferdinand
Piech, Siemens' CEO Heinrich von Pierer, Sara lee Corp. Chairman
John Bryan, General Motors Corp. President John Smith and General
Electric Co. Chairman John Welch.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Dead Sea Works and the Bromine Company, both
subsidiaries of Israel Chemicals, intend to acquire 80 percent
of a Czech firm engaged in pharmaceutical chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition price is estimated at 20 million U.S. dollars
and the factory will be built close to Prague, capital of the
Czech Republic, according to President of Dead Sea Works Ben Soon
quoted by local press today.
</P>
<P>
The decision to invest in an overseas company is due to the
government's decision to reduce benefits in the framework of the
Ministry of Industry and Trade's investment incentive program.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A total of 55 foreign institutions and funds have up
to now invested in Jordan's stock market, Jordan Times today
quoted an official from the Amman Financial Market (AFM) as saying
here.
</P>
<P>
Most of these institutions and funds which have recently
entered Jordan are from European countries and the United States,
said AFM Director General Wahib Shair.
</P>
<P>
He said that 19 non-Jordanian institutions invested at the AFM
last year compared with only nine in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Shair estimated that the total volume of non-Jordanian trading
at the AFM to be around 44 million Jordanian dinars (about 62
million U.S. dollars), of which about 26.5 million dinars (about
37.3 million dollars) was for purchasing transactions and less
than 18 million dinars (about 25 million dollars) for selling
deals.
</P>
<P>
AFM has been one of the most developed and fast growing stock
markets in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon imported 768 million U.S. dollars of
petroleum products in 1996, an increase of 22 percent over the
previous year, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The only English Language daily in the Lebanese capital of
Beirut said that Lebanon, which imports all its petroleum needs,
bought 4.2 million tonnes of oil products from Syria, Romania,
France and the Rotterdam oil market in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
