<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Hold Free Trade Talks with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January (Xinhua) -- South Africa's development
needs as well as those of its neighbors will have to be
recognized in any trade agreement with the European Union (EU),
the South African trade negotiation team members said today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director-General of the Foreign Affairs Ministry Abdul
Minty told reporters in Pretoria that South Africa is a young
democracy and its own development cannot take place in isolation
from the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
This will be the central message to the European Commission
when trade talks for a free trade agreement between South Africa
and the EU resume in Pretoria on January 24, said Minty.
</P>
<P>
According to a document on South Africa's stance of the talks,
scheduled to be formally presented to EU negotiators, the EU has
so far failed to recognize the integrated nature of the South
African economy with that of Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa called for a trade and development
agreement instead of a free trade agreement with the EU.
</P>
<P>
In terms of a EU mandate set out in March last year, 40
percent of South Africa's agricultural products are excluded from
the proposed agreement.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Chief Director of Foreign Trade Relations of
the Department of Trade and Industry, Faizel Ismail, said the
EU's mandate will bring into question the acceptability of such a
deal to the World Trade Organization, which requires at least 90
percent of all trade be included in such an agreement for
ratification.
</P>
<P>
Listing South Africa's other broad concerns, Ismail said the
EU has to take into account that the European economy is large
and competitive, therefore, adjustment costs in the South African
economy brought about by any free trade deal will have to be
addressed by mechanisms put into place by the EU.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Ambassador to the EU, Elias Links, who will
head his country's delegation, said the upcoming talks will set
the stage for intensive detailed negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"What must be understood is that there is underlying
seriousness on both sides to present an ultimate position to the
benefit of both sides, and in our case also to the region," said
Links. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
