<HEADLINE> Bats Could Carry Ebora Virus: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A South African researcher
said here today that bats could be carriers of the deadly Ebora virus.
</P>
<P>
The researcher, Robert Swanepoel, of the South African National
Institute for Virology, said, however, that more studies needed before
any definite conclusions can be drawn.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Broadcasting Association quoted the professor
as saying that his findings are based on scientific experiments
carried out on plants and a number of animal species.
</P>
<P>
He said of the animal tested, only bats were found to carry the
virus without falling ill.
</P>
<P>
Plants showed no sign of contracting the virus during the
experiments, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ebora is an extremely deadly disease found in Central Africa,
whose symptoms include fever, bloody diarrhoea and vomiting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
