<HEADLINE> Virtual Bank Launched in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's newest bank - the
branchless Citizens Bank of Canada - has opened its telephone
lines for business, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The bank, granted the federal charter Monday, enables clients
to do their banking by telephone, personal computer and automatic
teller machine 24 hours a day seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
Services will also be offered through the Internet once the
bank can solve some security concern, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
As a wholly owned subsidiary of Vancouver City Savings Credit
Union, Citizens Bank will start by focusing on the Toronto,
Calgary and Vancouver markets, providing clients with loans,
deposit accounts and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, a number of banks have already launched their own
electronic banking versions, it is reported.
</P>
<P>
"We're not opening up an electronic banking arm for a big bank.
We're something completely different," Linda Crompton, president
of the Vancouver-based electronic bank was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
As the name Citizens Bank suggests, it is a bank of the people,
"branchless, but not faceless," she said, adding that the bank
will offer financial services with a social conscience.
</P>
<P>
Crompton predicted that the new bank hopes to have 30,000 to
40,000 members by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Citizens Bank has assets of exceeding 450 million U.S. dollars.
Its parent company is the largest credit union in Canada with
226,000 members and 3.5 billion dollars in assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Women Earn 20 Pct Less Than Men: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- There is an average pay gap of
20 percent between Britain's women and men, and women will have to
wait another 45 years for equal pay if the current trend
continues, according to a report by the Equal Opportunities
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The study said that between 1975 and 1995 the average hourly
pay gap closed by 9 percent. If this trend continues, it will be
another 45 years before it disappears.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that pay difference are particularly wide
in managerial posts as female general managers and administrators
earn 42 percent less than their male colleagues and for women bank
and building society managers the gap is 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no equality of opportunity without equality in
pay. Throughout their working lives women earn less than men,
whether they are lawyers or sales assistants," said Kamlesh Bahl,
chairwoman of the commission.
</P>
<P>
She added that unless significant changes are made in the way
the pay gap is tackled, women face a future of continuing
inequality.
</P>
<P>
Women working part-time earn 58 percent of the hourly rate of
male full-timers. One in five of the population, most of them
women, now works part-time.
</P>
<P>
The pay gap is widest in the South-East where women earn on
average 22.1 percent less than men compared with the national
average of 20 percent. It is narrowest in Wales at 19 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
