<HEADLINE> Car Bomb Explosion Kills 6 in Central Algiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A car bomb attack by Islamic
extremists killed at least six people and wounded more than 40
this afternoon in the center of the Algerian capital of Algiers,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
This attack brought to 150 the number of victims killed since
the beginning of the Muslim festival of Ramadan this month, in an
unprecedented wave of massacres committed by the militant
movement, the Armed Islamic Group (GIA).
</P>
<P>
Shortly before 16:45 (1545 GMT), a Honda-Civic car packed with
explosives blew up near a passenger bus on the Boulevard des
Martyrs, a major thoroughfare of the city, the Agence France
Presse (AFP) quoted witnesses as saying.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that the boom of the explosion was heard in most parts
of central Algiers, and spread panic in the city, which has been
repeatedly hit by bombing attacks over the past 10 days after the
Ramadan began.
</P>
<P>
Houses lining on the two sides of the street were seriously
damaged and pieces of iron scraps were scattered on the pavement,
while the central Mustapha hospital was filled with the wounded,
including a five-year-old child whose eye was wounded, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Another car bomb explosion killed at least 21 people Sunday
evening in Algiers, according to official figures. Private sources
put the number of victims at 42.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Algerian press published today a communique
issued by the GIA vowing to continue the massacres and saying that
"there was no more neutrality in the war."
</P>
<P>
"The war will continue and intensify during the month of
Ramadan, and we have the means and men to punish those who are not
on our side," said the communique signed by the GIA chief, Antar
Zouabri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
