<HEADLINE> Kenya Set to Import Maize to Ensure Food Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today announced that his government has decided to import
maize to ensure food supply as Kenya was hit by a severe drought
during the past year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, the president noted that
many parts of the country were experiencing drought and hence
food shortage due to the failure of the short and long rains last
year.
</P>
<P>
A food situation report compiled by the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development said that about 1.5 million people
require relief food in Kenya following poor rains in the
vulnerable areas of eastern and northeastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the long rains maize production for 1996
is estimated at two million tons, a 20-percent decline compared
with 1995.
</P>
<P>
The overall cereal production in the country is estimated at
3.8 million tons for the 1996/97 marketing year while the total
consumption stands at 4.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In a new year address, Moi declared that the shortage of
staple food is one of the major challenges facing Kenya in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mike Sackett, the Director of the World Food Program to Kenya,
said recently that "the (food) situation in 1997 is the most
serious since the 1992/93 drought. If the next rains in March and
April fail, we have big problems."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government formally requested donor assistance
earlier this month following months of increase of food prices
and higher rates of malnutrition and infant mortality in
northeastern Kenya due to drought.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations disaster management team, which is on a
visit to Northeastern Province of Kenya, today learned that over
50 percent of livestock was wiped out by the drought and the
pastoral families run towards urban areas for survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
