<HEADLINE> Algerian to Be Named UN Central Africa Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Algerian diplomat
Mohamed Sahnoun, who once headed the U.N. operation in Somalia,
will be named a special representative for the Great Lakes region
of Central Africa, U.N. sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun was appointed to head the U.N. Somalia operation in
April 1992 but resigned in the following October after a row with
the then Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
He was rebuked by Boutros-Ghali for publicly saying the United
Nations came too late to save many of the millions of Somalis
facing starvation.
</P>
<P>
His diplomatic career has included service as Algeria's
ambassador to the United Nations in 1982-84, and to the United
States (1984-1989). He was deputy secretary-general of the Arab
League in 1973 and from 1964 to 1973 was deputy secretary-general
of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes region of Central Africa has been in turmoil
for the past three years following large-scale ethnic violence
between Hutus and Tutsis in Rwanda and Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
