<HEADLINE> Greenspan's Speech Boosts European Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major stock markets
in Europe recovered from their morning losses and ended
positively, boosted by U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan's upbeat assessment of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Bank of England Eddie George's call Monday
night for a rate hike to ensure that government inflation targets
are met cast a shadow over morning dealings on the London market.
</P>
<P>
But share prices bounced off their lows when the Dow shook off
an early bout of profit-taking to push higher, with the FTSE 100
index closing 1.5 points up at 4,195.5 after a low of 4,167.6.
</P>
<P>
On the Frankfurt market, profit-taking after recent strong
gains made the DAX-30 index sharply lower at the close, down 53.97
points at 2,976.71, falling through the 3,000 points level.
</P>
<P>
The Paris bourse had also fallen to a session low of 2,384.77
in the morning before taking heart from Greenspan and finishing up
3.78 points at 2,409.88.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares closed up 1.5
points at 4,195.5. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index ended down 53.97
points at 2,976.71. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished 3.78
points up at 2,409.88. 
