<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Junxia Sick, Coach Reveals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China's Wang Junxia, world
record holder for the women's 10,000 meters and 5,000m winner at
the Atlanta Olympics, has been plagued by an illness in the past
two months, her coach Mao Dezhen told Xinhua through telephone
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"She was overtired after the Olympics, and the doctor said she
had contracted a nervous disorder, forcing her out of regular
training in the past few months," said Mao, who is now training
his other runners in China's southern city Nanning.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who won the Jesse Owens Award of 1993 due to a series of
brilliant record-beating performances and became the best distance
runner of the world under the coaching of her former trainer Ma
Junren, competed bravely in the 10,000m and 5,000m in Atlanta. The
23-year-old slim girl was the only distance runner, men and female
in the world, to challeng the humid and hot weather of Atlanta in
the above events, winning the silver medal in the 25-lap final and
the gold in the next.
</P>
<P>
It is the only athletics gold medal for China in the Games, and
Wang was hailed as a national heroine after the victory.
</P>
<P>
"She had to get involved in many celebrations and fatigued
social activitities, that costed her a lot of time and energy,"
Mao revealed.
</P>
<P>
It was said that Wang was given about 50,000 U.S. dollars as
prize money from the country and a few Hong Kong businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Wang had to spend some time to get back her bonus - a Mercedes
Benz won at the world championships in Stuttgart in 1993.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that though the car belongs to Wang, yet it is
still seized by Ma Junren. Wang broke away from Ma with a field of
world class female runners in 1994 due to some bitter dispute.
</P>
<P>
"Every time she runs, headaches and leg injury make it
difficult for her to bear up. She needs a good rest. She may drop
out of the National Games this September in Shanghai, but she will
try her best to continue her career," Mao said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Dong, former world 1,500m champion in 1993, has joined
Mao's group after a long lay-off. Liu left Ma as soon as she won
the world title, and failed to make a comeback in the Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
According to Mao, Wang is maintaining a convalescent training
program in Shenyang. "She plans to come to Nanning in the end of
this month. We will have our winter training in this warm city
instead of going to Kunming's plateau camp," the coach said.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to say if Wang takes part in this year's world
championships or not. Wang once expressed that she would like to
study in a university, but most people encourage her to run
ahead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
