<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Latvia's Finance Minister
Vassilija Melnik today resigned over conflict-of-interest
allegations that had also prompted Prime Minister Andris Skele to
offer his resignation Monday, Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Melnik was nominated as finance minister by Skele, but was
attacked by parliament members and President Guntis Ulmanis for
accepting posts on the boards of the Latvian port authority and
several companies.
</P>
<P>
Parliament approved Melnik's appointment anyway last week. But
Skele, originally a businessman with no party affiliation, said he
took the allegations as an insult to his dignity and offered to
resign on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The parliament and President Ulmanis are now negotiating over
who should be nominated as new prime minister. Interfax said that
Skele, appointed prime minister in December 1995, could be asked
to stay on. 
