<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Pass Campaign-Finance Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
urged Congress on Tuesday to enact campaign-finance reform
legislation to bar foreign donations as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
"Delay will mean the death of reform one more time," Clinton
said in an address before a meeting of the Democratic National
Committee (DNC).
</P>
<P>
"So I ask members of Congress in both parties to act now while
the public is watching, while the momentum is building," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DNC announced that the party would no longer
accept contributions from foreigners or the American subsidiaries
of foreign companies, and put a 100,000 U.S. dollar cap on all
future "soft-money" donations.
</P>
<P>
In his first post-inaugural address to the DNC, Clinton called
on Republicans to join Democrats in refusing so-called
"soft-money" -- unregulated contributions to parties that can
be used for a range of party-building activities.
</P>
<P>
"If you will do it, we will do it," he said. "We have offered
our hand time and again. Why not just say yes?"
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed his support for a long-stalled
campaign-finance bill sponsored by Arizona Republican Senator John
McCain Wisconsin Democrat Senator Russell Feingold. 
</P>
