<HEADLINE> South African Chief Resigns after Damning Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- South African Football
Association executive president Solomon Morewa resigned on
Wednesday after a damning report described him as unfit to run
soccer in the country, according to a report here.
</P>
<P>
Morewa, 54, announced his resignation eight days after the
release of a judical commission into the running of South African
soccer, which recommended he stepped down.
</P>
<P>
Morewa was heavily criticised in the 102-page report by
Justice Benjamin Poickard, who was mandated in May by sports
minister Steve Tshwete to investigate possible corruption in
South African soccer.
</P>
<P>
The investigation found Morewa had received a loan of
500,000 rand ($107,000) from a marketing company granted the
rights to organise international matches for the South African
national team and a Mercedes Benz car from a tournament sponsor.
</P>
<P>
He was also found to have awarded himself a study bursary
from a football association fund specifically designed to
finance players' education and bonus payments following South
Africa's win in last year's African Nations Cup.
</P>
<P>
The commission said: "He has proven himself to be over
concerned with promoting his own interests instead of those of
his association and should resign."
</P>
<P>
Morewa told radio interviewers he had not discussed the
matter with FIFA at its annual award ceremony in Lisbon on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
But a FIFA press release from Zurich said he had a meeting on
the issue with FIFA president Joao Havelange and secretary-general
Sepp Blatter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
