<HEADLINE> More Chinese Enterprises Expected To Comply With ISO Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China issued its first ISO
14000 certificates to four companies today, demonstrating that it
has made a great step forward in increasing use of the standards
of the International Standards Organization.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the ISO 14000 is to curb pollution and waste, an
official with the State Bureau of Environmental Protection
explained.
</P>
<P>
China is a developing country with many poorly-equipped
factories, the official noted, and although it closed over 57,000
factories last year because they were causing serious pollution,
those remaining are one of the main sources of pollution and they
waste a lot of energy.
</P>
<P>
The standards will make China's environmental protection work
more scientific and effective, he pointed out, and it is one of
China's important moves in preventing pollution.
</P>
<P>
"China will take action, but carefully, to expand the use of
the ISO 14000 standards with regard to the country's situation,"
said Xie Zhenhua, director of the bureau, and called on
enterprises to abide by environmental protection laws and
regulations and to comply with the government standards.
</P>
<P>
"The first four certified enterprises are all modern," he
commented, and that certification work will be extended to more
factories, including backward ones, and 22 are awaiting
certification now.
</P>
<P>
The companies recognized today were the ABB Xiamen Switchgear
Co. Ltd, the Shanghai Gao Qiao-BASF Dispersion Co. Ltd, the Haier
Group's Haier Refrigerator System, and the Beijing Matsushita
Color CRT Co. Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
