<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Mechanism Discusses Situation in Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The central organ of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Mechanism for Conflict
Prevention, Management and Resolution held its 28th ordinary
session last Monday to discuss the situation in the Great Lakes
Region.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued today said that the central organ
expressed its deep concern about the continued fighting in
eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reaffirmed the fundamental principles of the
terri- torial integrity of Zaire and the respect of the borders
inherited from colonization, as stated in the charter of the OAU
and the resolution adopted in Cairo of Egypt, in July 1964.
</P>
<P>
It also reaffirmed the principle of absolute respect of rights
to nationality and citizenship of all the peoples established
within internationally recognized borders, in conformity with the
African charter on human and peoples' rights and other relevant
international legal instruments.
</P>
<P>
The cenhral organ underscored the urgent need for the OAU to
intensify its efforts with a view to helping find a peaceful
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the OAU to send a high level delegation to
Zaire and the other states of the region to particularly mark the
concern of the OAU about the crisis that is ravaging eastern
Zaire and the determination of the organization to contribute to
the search for a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
The meeting called upon the OAU Secretary General to intensify
efforts aimed at ensuring, in concert with the international
community, a closer follow up of the evolution of the situation
and to take the necessary measures that will guarantee a better
coordinatcon of initiatives taken to find a solution to the
crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the situation in Burundi, the central organ
condemned severely the recent massacre of more than 120 Hutus
soon after their return to Burundi from Tanzania where they were
living as refugees.
</P>
<P>
Within that context, the meeting stressed its support for the
sanctions adopted by the countries of the region against Burundi
so as to exert pressure on the Bujumbura regimd to bring it to
hold unconditional negotiations with all the parties involved
with a view to finding a peaceful solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting expressed satisfaction at the massive return of
Rwandese refugees who were in Zaire and Tanzania and appealed to
the OAU member states and the international community to support
the efforts made by the Rwandan government to resettle those
refugees and to rehabilitate the judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
