<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan Sees First Growth in GDP in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyzstan's gross domestic
product (GDP) rose 5.6 percent to 22.47 billion som (about 1.32
billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, the first increase in the five
years since independence in late 1991, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the State Statistics Commission showed industrial
output rose 4.6 percent to 9.93 billion som (about 584 million
dollars) in 1996 over 1995, while agricultural production jumped
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Grain output soared 45 percent, making 1996 the first year
Kyrgyzstan stopped importing grain.
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that 77,000 people were registered as
unemployed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Radical economic reforms in this former Soviet Republic of 4.6
million people are believed to have caused severe economic and
social problems as the transition to a market economy got underway
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The economy slid into recession as GDP fell steeply, inflation
rocketed, foreign debt rose and living standards fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
But by 1995, as reforms started to slow down, the country's
economic situation started to improve slowly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
