<HEADLINE> HK Hotel Owners Optimistic About Prospects After Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Hotel owners here are
optimistic about the future of Hong Kong after its handover later
this year, the chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Hotel
Owners said here today.
</P>
<P>
"With the handover this year and the start of operation of the
New Airport next year, Hong Kong's status as an international
tourist city will for sure be strengthened," Lui Che Woo said at a
press conference before the start of the federation's annual
general meeting here.
</P>
<P>
And more international meetings are expected to be held here
and Hong Kong's hotel industry is to face an even bigger challenge
as more tourists will come, he said.
</P>
<P>
"At the turn of the century, Hong Kong's position will become
even more strategic with Asia's growing importance in the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
"In order to ensure our competitiveness in the world as well as
in the Asian market, we must strike a balance in the local hotel
operation and make sure that we do not price ourselves out of the
market," he warned.
</P>
<P>
More hotels should be built to cater to budget visitors, but an
over supply of new hotel rooms can also be detrimental to the
local hotel industry and the overall economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"A right balance should therefore be achieved," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lui encouraged the government to work together with the
industry to ensure that a positive image and appeal is projected
to tourists worldwide, in particular, after the handover in July.
</P>
<P>
The federation supports the Hong Kong Tourist Association's
initiatives to build theme parks and tourist attractions to
encourage a longer stay of tourists in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The organization hopes that a department or bureau of tourism
will be set up to ensure this second largest foreign exchange
earner is adequately taken care of, he added.
</P>
<P>
More than 16,000 hotel rooms are to be built by the year 2000
and with the current figure of 33,491, they could help ease the
shortage of rooms in the hotel industry, federation officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The federation plans to conduct a study on the development of
Hong Kong's tourism and hotel industries as well as ways to ensure
that room supply keeps up with demand.
</P>
<P>
Federation officials also hoped to meet Tung Chee-hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, before
the handover to brief him on the problems facing the future of the
industry and work out a coherent tourism policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
