<HEADLINE> Walkie-Talkie Becomes Communication Tools for Herdsmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Across the vast grasslands of
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, mobile phones are no longer used
just by public security men.
</P>
<P>
The cellular age has become a communication instrument for
herdsmen to report to local police when their cattle are stolen.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, a number of towns in the Xilin Gol League and
Ulanqab League collected over one million yuan (120,000
U.S. dollars) to build nearly 100 radio communication stations
covering the vast pastoral areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 herdsman households have now bought mobile
phones.
</P>
<P>
As the network is connected to the public security departments,
herdsmen can report thefts to the local police, and report their
safe and sound conditions regularly to the town stations by using
their phones.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years Siziwang Banner (Ulan Hua Town)
resolved 136 criminal cases, with 87 offenders arrested and 310
stolen cattle returned, thanks to the communication network by
which the public security departments promptly got details of
offenders appearances and other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
A herdsman lost six horses and asked for help from the township
public security department with his walkie-talkie, and his horses
were quickly found in an area 70 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
Mobile phones also act as a "hot line" for rescuing patients
and reporting major fires. Only in last year, 70 people with
serious diseases were also rescued in Xilin Gol League thanks to
the walkie-talkies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, herdsmen use the communication tool to exchange
informations on cattle prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
