<HEADLINE> Railway Strike Disrupts Uganda-Kenya Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The railway workers' strike in
Tororo, a small Ugandan town bordering Kenya, has severely
disrupted movement of personnel and goods from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said cargo wagons piled up at the
Kenyan boder post of Malaba and the Uganda Tororo railways yard.
</P>
<P>
About 400 workers laid down their tools on Monday morning in
response to a strongly worded notice glued on the station walls,
trees and other places in support of the strike.
</P>
<P>
They said they went on strike to protest delayed salaries for
the last three months of 1996 and to demand for salary increment.
</P>
<P>
The police patrolled the Tororo railway yard where over 300
cargo wagons and fuel tankers destined for kampala and mombasa
are parked.
</P>
<P>
On the Kenyan side of Malaba, a Kenyan Railways worker said
105 cargo wagons belonging to Ugandan importers could not be
taken to Tororo because of strike.
</P>
<P>
In another development, workers of the Uganda Railways
Corporation in Jinja, 100 km west of Tororo, also went on strike
on Tuesday, demanding arrears of salary since last November, and
other accumulated arrears dating back to 1992 and improvement in
welfare. 
</P>
