<HEADLINE> Four More Foreign Banks in China Doing RMB Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Four foreign-funded banks in
Shanghai have been given permission to deal in yuan after they
move to the Pudong New Development Area, the People's Bank of
China Shanghai branch announced today.
</P>
<P>
The four are the Shanghai branch of Japan's Daiichi Kangyo Bank
and Sanwa Bank Ltd., Britain's Standard Chartered, and the
Shanghai-Paris International Bank, the first joint venture bank in
Shanghai, set up in 1992 by the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China and France's Banque Nationale de Paris.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Shanghai gave permission to deal in RMB (yuan) to
four foreign banks. The eight are required to relocate in the
Pudong area before they can start dealing in RMB. The business
includes savings, loans, loan guarantees, and investment in state
treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
They are also allowed to open sub-branches in the Puxi area, or
in downtown Shanghai for foreign exchange business.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China Shanghai branch said that it is now
working hard to come up with policies and regulations to guide the
RMB business of foreign banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
