</P>
<P>
-- The House voted 395 to 28 reprimand Speaker Newt Gingrich
and fine him 300,000 U.S. dollars as it endorsed the ethics
committee finding that he had brought discredit on the institution
by using tax-exempt money for partisan purposes.
</P>
<P>
-- A condition for Poland's joining NATO, that its military be
put under civilian control, has angered Poland's top commander,
who objects to losing authority.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Democratic National Committee officials announced Tuesday
that the party no longer will accept contributions from foreign
nationals or the American subsidiaries of foreign corporations and
will put a 100,000 cap on all Future "soft money" donations.
</P>
<P>
-- South Korean President Kim Young Sam agreed Tuesday to
reconsider new labor and security laws that his party rammed
through parliament on December 26, a surprise conciliatory move
aimed at ending nearly a month of strikes and protests that have
cost the nation more than 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton said his budget will call for Medicare savings of
138 billion U.S. dollars over six years, which is midway between
the sums he and the GOP proposed in last year's budget deadlock.
Republicans welcomed the announcement, but leaders now want 193.5
billion in tax cuts through 2002, more than the previous plan.
</P>
