<HEADLINE> Measles Kills 14 in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen children, most of them
below five years old, have died of measles complications in Manila
since January 1, the Department of Health said today.
</P>
<P>
The department said the number of measles-stricken children
admitted into San Lazaro Hospital in the country's capital city
surged from 335 to 507, most of them under five years old, within
the past six days.
</P>
<P>
The department denied there is a measles outbreak and predicted
cases will peak from February to April.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica appealed to mothers to have
their nine to 11 months old children immunized against measles, a
highly contagious viral disease transmitted through nose and
throat discharges and affecting mostly children.
</P>
<P>
Measles immunization is given free in all health centers
nationwide, Reodica said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Eric Tayag, chief epidemiologist at San Lazaro Hospital,
said the latest deaths occurred Tuesday -- two children aged six
months and one year respectively.
</P>
<P>
From January to December last year, 5,365 measles cases, with
293 deaths, were admitted into San Lazaro Hospital, the country's
main contagious disease hospital, according to Tayag.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
