<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen to Launch Giant Gas project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Deputy Prime Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-attar has said a giant gas project to be
launched in mid 1997 would greatly boost Yemen's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Yemeni newspaper Al-Thawra which was
published today, al-attar, who is also Oil Minister, said the
4.5-billion-dollar project includes extending a 320-kilometer
pipeline from Maareb in the north to Belhaf on the coast of
Arabian Sea; setting up a gas factory at a cost of more than 300
million U.S. dollars and constructing an exportation terminal in
Belhalf.
</P>
<P>
After completion, the project will provide enough energy to
operate two thermal power plants in Maareb and Belhalf with a
power ranging from 180 to 200 megawatts, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not name companies which had signed contracts
to launch the project, neither mentioned sources of the huge
investment. But he said exportation of the gas produced by the
project will start in the year 2001 at a rate of 5 million tons a
year. And Yemen has so far received orders from Turkey, Japan and
Korea to purchase its gas .
</P>
<P>
Yemen has recently signed agreements with British, Indonesian
and U.S. firms for searching and prospecting for oil in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable studies, Yemen's gas reserve ranges
between 13 and 15 trillion cubic feet. Yemen is thinking of
exporting liquefied gas to neighboring countries, such
as Somalia, Sudan and Djibouti after meeting domestic needs.
</P>
<P>
At current prices, Yemen will be able to obtain 500 million
U.S. dollars a year in oil revenues for 25 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
