<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Approves Full Deregulation of Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
signed here today an executive order approving the full
deregulation of the country's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The measure, effective from February 8, will relieve the
government of the burden of determining the prices of gasoline and
other petroleum products, which will now be set by oil companies.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his regular press conference in the Presidential
Palace, Ramos said the measure is aimed at fostering "a truly
competitive market which can better achieve the social policy
objectives of fair prices and adequate, continuous supply of
environmentally-clean and high quality petroleum products."
</P>
<P>
He cited the stable prices of crude oil and petroleum products
in the world market as well as the stable exchange rate between
peso and U.S. dollar as the reasons for his approval of the
measure.
</P>
<P>
The price of crude oil had been stable at 21-23 U.S. dollars
per barrel since last October while the prices of petroleum
products in the world market had been stable since mid-December
last year.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the peso against U.S. dollar has also been
stable for the past 12 months, averaging around 26.2 pesos to one
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the deregulation of the oil industry, based on
studies made by the Department of Energy, would keep oil prices in
the country at "very manageable levels" because of the entry of
other players in the downstream industry.
</P>
<P>
Energy Secretary Francisco Viray also shared the same view. He
said that oil prices will be "at a stable level and fuel oil price
change will be minimal."
</P>
<P>
He added that the deregulation does not mean the government
will give up total control of the industry.
</P>
<P>
It still has to intervene in matters affecting fair trade
practices, security of domestic oil supply, public health and
safety and environmental protection, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Germany to Expand Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Germany today
agreed to expand bilateral ties by increasing cultural and
educational exchange programs, as well as enhancing trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We must now think of an expanded relationship that is not
confined to trade but also includes education and science and
technology cooperation," Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah
Badawi told a news conference after talks with visiting German
Vice-Chancellor and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel here.
</P>
<P>
Germany proposed that the two countries sign a cultural
agreement to boost bilateral ties, which Abdullah termed as
"good".
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who arrived here earlier today for a two-day visit, is
the first German foreign minister to visit Malaysia in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Kinkel assured him that Bonn was willing to
participate with Malaysia in programs that would enable it to
transfer its technology.
</P>
<P>
He said they also discussed regional and international issues
such as ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) and
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Kinkel responded positively to a proposal that
Malaysia and Germany form a partnership to help in the
reconstruction of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On Bonn's bid to secure a permanent seat on the U.N. Security
Council, he said Germany was "well qualified" for the job.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he also informed Kinkel that Malaysia was not
ready to discuss the reform of the U.N. on a "piecemeal basis but
in a package formula" which covers all issues and areas of the
world body.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also met with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
and Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim here today.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with Anwar, Kinkel said
his meetings with the Malaysian leaders were "satisfactory."
</P>
<P>
Describing Malaysia as a "booming tiger", Kinkel praised
Malaysia's economic achievements and offered German assistance in
high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the fifth largest trading partner of Malaysia.
According to official statistics, two-way trade in the first six
months of 1996 amounted to 7.05 billion ringgit (about 2.82
billion U.S. dollars) against 6.77 billion ringgit (about 2.71
billion U.S. dollars) in the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Germany registered a surplus of 1.15 billion ringgit (about 460
million U.S. dollars) in the first half of last year compared with
1.23 billion ringgit (about 490 million U.S. dollars) in the
previous corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, German companies have invested about 1.6 billion
ringgit (about 640 million U.S. dollars) in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
There are currently more than 200 German companies in Malaysia
and about 90 percent of them have production facilities in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Cuts Key Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy's central bank slashed two
key lending rates last night following the release of figures
showing the inflation rate had steadied at 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The discount rate was cut by 0.75 percentage points to 6.75
percent and the Lombard rate was cut from 9 percent to 8.25
percent.
</P>
<P>
The substantial cut in lending rates followed provisional
inflation data for January released Tuesday by the National
Institute for Statistics, which forecast a price index of 2.6
percent in January, level with December's rate.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past few months, inflation has remained at moderate
levels in line with the targets for the present year," a statement
from the Central Bank said, adding that "long term market rates
are consistent with falling inflation."
</P>
<P>
"The Bank of Italy will continue to watch developments in
demand, the cost of labor and price policies. Monetary policy
will continue to be aimed at creating long term stability in the
currency's purchasing power," the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
