<HEADLINE> Ramos Hopeful of Ceasefire Between Government, Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Despite sporadic clashes between
the Philippine government troops and the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), Philippine President Ramos is still optimistic about
a ceasefire prior to the holding of formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said at his weekly news conference this afternoon that
the government peace negotiators will follow the general peace
process formula similar to the one adopted by the government when
it concluded a successful peace talks with the Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF).
</P>
<P>
"We are at the stage vis-a-vis the MILF right now the same as
where we were in October 1992 and we are not yet really into
formal talks but the work is being done at the committee level,
below the level of the negotiators so that they can provide the
proper environment for a final agreement," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that when the peace process between the government
and the MNLF started in 1992, the first step was to achieve a
local ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"We did that during the MNLF process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that by local ceasefire, in the case of the MILF, it
refers to such areas as Malmar, Cabulnan and perhaps Basilan. A
general ceasefire must be reached first, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Most of the MILF forces are operating in Central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"I hope it will be done through the efforts of our panel and
the MILF panel with the support of a lot of people, including our
peace constituency in Mindanao which has already expanded," the
president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
