<HEADLINE> India to Help But Not Interfere in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Indian Foreign
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral said here today that his country will
help Sri Lanka in whatever way it could but will not interfere in
its affairs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, he said India
will not interfere. But whenever and whatever help Sri Lanka needs
from India will be placed at Sri Lanka's disposal.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that it is in India's interest to see Sri Lanka's
ethnic conflict brought to an end, but his country has no
intention to intervene in the issue.
</P>
<P>
India follows the principle of good neighborliness and it
respects the sovereignty of all its neighbors, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Gujral, who co-chaired the third session of the Indo-Lanka
Joint Commission, expressed satisfaction at what has been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
"A great deal of flesh and teeth has been given to the economy,
science and technology and culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of this month, talks are to be held in India on
civil aviation and soon it could be hoped that travel between the
two countries will increase to the benefit of both.
</P>
<P>
The minister said India has offered a second tranche of a
credit line of 15 million Indian rupees in addition to what had
been offered earlier. Additionally a sum of 50 million rupees was
offered for rehabilitation work in North and East Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Gujral described the Indo-Sri Lanka relationship as cordial,
friendly, open and frank and said he was satisfied and happy with
the results of his visit here.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar said that at
the meeting here, there were dramatic achievements for the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the process of consultation between the two
countries has gone on for over two years now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
