<HEADLINE> Italian PM to Visit Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi is to visit the Middle East at the invitation of Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat who is currently visiting Italy, a government
statement said today.
</P>
<P>
No dates were given for the trip.
</P>
<P>
This was Arafat's first meeting with a European leader since
the Palestinians signed an accord with Israel on January 17 on the
redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
During a half-hour meeting at the prime minister's office, the
two leaders discussed the ongoing Middle East peace process. Prodi
asked about the next step in the process now the Hebron agreement
has been signed.
</P>
<P>
The Hebron accord was signed after months of negotiation. Under
the deal, 80 percent of the town will revert to Palestinian
control, ending 30 years of Israeli rule.
</P>
<P>
Arafat stressed the importance of a rapid and punctual
implementation of the Hebron agreement and expressed his
appreciation for the role Italy and the European Union played in
helping reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the two leaders agreed that the
peace process should be accompanied by economic development
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
This is Arafat's second meeting with Prodi in two months. The
Palestinian leader came to Rome for a meeting of the Socialist
International Council in December 1996 and visited political
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
