<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Quick Passage of Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today called on the bicameral Congress to pass the 1997 budget
soon in order not to jeopardize major infrastructure projects,
particularly those with foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting of the Legislative-Executive Development
Advisory Council, Ramos urged the House of Representatives and the
Senate to continue their dialogue on the budget.
</P>
<P>
He said the 30 billion pesos (1.2 billion US dollars) proposed
infrastructure projects for 1997, including the vital Ninoy Aquino
Highway, will be adversely affected by the delay in the passage of
the new budget.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives and the Senate have been
deadlocked over the passage of the budget for nearly three months
because of wide differences on the cuts in the Countrywide
Development Funds.
</P>
<P>
The house has refused to accept any cuts in the Countrywide
Development Funds, or the so-called "pork barrels", as proposed by
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The development funds are vital for the representatives since
their popularity usually depends on budget allocations for
infrastructure funds for their districts.
</P>
<P>
But the senators rely more on campaign donations than the pork
barrels to ensure their re-election in the 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
