<HEADLINE> China to Hold World Gardening Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China is to hold an
international garden exposition, the first of its kind in the
country, from May to October, 1999, it was announced in Beijing
today.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the exposition will be "Man and Nature -- Entering
the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
To be hold in Kunming, the capital of southwest China's Yunnan
Province, where more than 18,000 different plants grow in
tropical, sub-tropical, temperate and rigid zones, the exposition
will cover an area of 218 hectares, including 63 hectares of
spectacular floral displays.
</P>
<P>
Various exhibits will be displayed, including horticultural
products, plants, flowers, fruit, vegetables, green land, gardens
and related technology, equipment, books, stamps, post cards and
other items.
</P>
<P>
International expositions, an event organized by governments of
different countries or agencies, enjoy a history of more than 100
years. Some 40 different expositions have been hosted by many
countries since the first one was held in London in 1851. The
exposition to be held in Kunming is designated as a Class A1 event.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government values very much the opportunity to host
such an important world-level exposition and is determined to make
it a success," said Liu Jing, secretary-general of the National
Organizing Committee of the '99 Kunming International Gardening
Exposition, and also vice-governor of Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, Premier Li Peng sent invitation letters to
leaders of countries around the world at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Liu also expressed his hope that countries across the world and
international organizations will visit the exposition to promote
mutual understanding and co-operation between all countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
