<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul to Press Japan to Set Up Body on "Comfort Women" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean legislators and
civic leaders will go to Japan next week to press the Japanese
parliament to set up an investigative committee on "comfort women"
who were forced to serve at the Japanese army brothels during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Chongdaehyop, a council for the comfort women, and other social
organizations will visit Japan between February 3 and 7 along with
lawmakers for a series of meetings with their Japanese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Delegation members said here today that they will press
Japanese lawmakers to form an investigative panel within their
parliament to find out the facts behind the operation involving
such women and to press Tokyo to officially apologize and
compensate the victims.
</P>
<P>
They will also lodge a protest against Japan's Asian Peace Fund
of Women, which has secretly delivered monetary compensation to
South Korean victims in defiance of Seoul's opposition.
</P>
<P>
Historians say that as many as 200,000 women, mostly Koreans,
were recruited as "comfort women" -- a euphemism for sex slaves --
for the Japanese imperial army at it invaded East and Southeast
Asia in the 1930s and the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Japan ruled the Korean Peninsula as a colony from 1910 until
its World War II defeat in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese private organization, Asian Peace Fund for Women,
recently relayed 2 million Japanese yen (about 15,009
U.S. dollars) to each of five former South Korean "comfort women"
with a letter of apology from Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government has strongly demanded that Japan
make government-level compensation to "comfort women" and stop
providing compensation money to the victims through a private
fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railways Responsible for Train-Van Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The train-van collision which
happened Tuesday near Gujar Khan, Rawalpindi, was due to gross
neglect and mismanagement by the railway authorities, a religious
party charged today.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Hafiz Muhammad Idrees, Punjab chief of the
Jammat-e-Islami said the railway authorities should be responsible
for Tuesday's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
A passenger train rammed into a school van at a railroad
crossing near Gujar Khan Tuesday morning, killing nine people
including six children and injuring seven others as it tore the
van apart.
</P>
<P>
Idrees said it was amazing that the railway authorities had
never thought of installing gates on unmanned crossings and
posting guards there.
</P>
<P>
Idrees quoted newspaper reports as saying there are around
3,700 unmanned crossings on different rail tracks all over the
country, causing huge life losses, but the railway authorities
paid no heed to this.
</P>
<P>
Idrees called upon the authorities concerned to take
appropriate steps to check the recurrence of such bloody incidents
in the future on a priority basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
