<HEADLINE> Verdict on Benazir's Petition Expected Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Pakistan
is expected to announce its judgment on January 29 in Benazir
Bhutto's petition against the dismissal of her government.
</P>
<P>
A seven-member bench of the court, headed by Chief Justice
Sajjad Ali Shah, gave eight days to Benazir's counsel Alitzaz
Ahsan to defend her against the dissolution of her government by
President Farooq Leghari on November 5, 1996, court sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
Ahsan submitted his arguments before the court from January 13
to 22. Altogether he availed more than 24 hours to present his
case. On the last day of his presentation he was given one hour
extra.
</P>
<P>
According to the time-frame set by the court, from Saturday the
President's counsel Khalid Anwar will present his arguments for
substantiating the charges made in the dissolution order.
</P>
<P>
The court has allowed Anwar three days from January 25 to 27 to
conclude his arguments.
</P>
<P>
The court has fixed January 28 again for Bhutto's counsel
Aitzaz Ahsan to exercise his right of reply. On the following day,
the Supreme Court may give its verdict.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto filed her first petition one week after the dismissal of
her government. The Supreme Court had already rejected her
petition twice, claiming improper language was used in the
petition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
