<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key to National Unity in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The formation of a unified army
is key to national unity and reconciliation in Angola in the
post-war era, Joao De Matos, Chief of the General Staff of the
armed forces, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Matos made the remarks in a ceremony to mark the 21st
anniversary of the Angolan air force.
</P>
<P>
Three days before the establishment of the national unity
government which is scheduled for January 25, the formation of a
united army is essential to a lasting peace in the southern
African country after 20 years of civil war, said Matos.
</P>
<P>
The general stressed that it would create peaceful atmosphere
for the former rebels of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) to join the unified army.
</P>
<P>
According to the Lusaka Peace Accord, an estimated 26,300
UNITA soldiers would join the unified army. The process is
nearly completed by now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
