<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- At the Zairean town of Tingui-Tingui, 150 kilometers east of
Kisangani, about 100,000 Rwandan refugees have finally emerged
from the jungle after months of wandering. The refugees,
originally from the Mugunga refugee camp in eastern Zaire, have
trekked 700 kilometers and survived by eating plants during the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
-- The Algerian capital Algiers was hit by two car bomb attacks
on Tuesday, in which at least 17 people were killed and 50
wounded. The attacks took place after 42 people were killed and 35
wounded in an explosion at the populous neighborhood of Belcourt
in Algiers Sunday evening. The militant group, Armed Islamic
Group, has threatened to "continue and intensify" the massacre of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- By signing on Tuesday the German-Czech reconciliation
declaration, Helmut Kohl and Vaclav Klaus have settled the last
problem between Germany and Eastern European countries. But the
text also indirectly ratified the expulsion of more than 3 million
ethnic German minority population -- one third of the population
of Czechoslovakia in 1945 -- by Prague 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Among the 10,000 youths who win doctoral degrees each year
in France, 2,000 of them have to stay on in the laboratories of
their colleges for one or two years as post-doctoral fellows,
because of lack of job opportunities outside. More and more of
them are going abroad to seek jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
