<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in 10 Chinese Urban Families Have Personal Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese families have placed
personal computers on their list of household essentials.
</P>
<P>
Computers come after color TVs, refrigerators and washing
machines as a necessary appliance for urban homes.
</P>
<P>
Yang Tianxing, director at the Computer Department of the
Ministry of the Electronic Industry, said that one-in-ten of the
country's urban Chinese families now have personal computers.
</P>
<P>
Last year up to 40 percent of the computers sold on the Chinese
market were bought by Chinese families.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the development of computers and wide use of
multimedia technologies have quickened the pace of making
computers popular among ordinary Chinese families.
</P>
<P>
Most individual PC owners in China are intellectuals and
computer technicians because computers are a hi-tech product, Yang
noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China's potential PC market capacity is as
huge as the annual market for color TV sets, currently 20 million
units year.
</P>
<P>
Ministry's statistics show that the country's PC sales hit 1.8
million units last year, up 56 percent over the previous
year. Total computer sales reached 80 billion yuan in 1996, a
30 percent increase over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The country's PC sales are expected to hit between 2.4 and 2.7
million units in 1997, with the total sales value topping 40
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that Chinese-made personal computers are cheaper
and more convenient in post-sale services than the imported
models, while their functions and quality are the same.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Chinese products have claimed an increasing large
market share. In 1995, Chinese-made PCs gained a market share of
15 percent, while in 1996, PCs with such famed brands as Legend,
Great Wall, Tongchuang and Langchao had 40 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that Pentium-based computers will occupy a
market share of 80 percent in 1997 with the rest by 486 types. In
the meantime, 386-computers will be squeezed out of the market
completely.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
