<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adoption of Unitary Rating on Firms Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese bankers have suggested
the government create a unified rating system for domestic
enterprises, to give banks a common standard by which to evaluate
firms which apply for loans.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion was repeatedly raised by participants in last
week's national financial conference and at separate annual
meetings of local branch heads held by the country's major
state-owned commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
To date, there has been no such a national criterion for
assessing the reputation of enterprises in China, owing to the
long-established planned economy and differing ideology. This has
resulted in bad credit in many cases and numerous bad loans,
according to the bankers.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese bankers have to set their own standards for
classifying firms, which is in the long-term interests of both
enterprises and banks, and also the state, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bankers, the credit-rating for Chinese
enterprises, also including banks, currently depends on some
international organizations which evaluate Chinese firms by mainly
judging their relationship with the government.
</P>
<P>
The ratings for state-owned commercial banks have declined
since 1994, when China started to separate policy-oriented loans
from commercial loans by setting up three policy banks. Meanwhile,
the policy banks such as the Import and Export Bank of China
continue to be rated as AA-, which is equal to the government's
rating.
</P>
<P>
"These ratings cannot reflect the real situation in China's
banking industry, the country's ongoing banking reform and its
efforts to commercialize and internationalize the state-owned
commercial banks," the bankers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
