<HEADLINE> Acute Diarrhoea Breaks Out in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Acute diarrhoea and cholera
have emerged in Somali capital Mogadishu, leaving more than 10
died in the past two weeks and hundreds ill, said the local
health authorities.
</P>
<P>
Sample tests from a number of cases revealed the presence of
cholera epidemic here, said the authorities.
</P>
<P>
One of the dead was a well known Somali journalist called
Mohamed Ahmed Takow.
</P>
<P>
The SOS hospital, the major child and maternity hospital in
the city, registered nearly 300 cases of acute diarrhoea since
the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Jumale Abdi, a pediatrician at Al-Arafat Medical
Center, said his hospital had admitted 26 patients, mainly women
and children and 15 of them suffered from cholera.
</P>
<P>
Abdi said the number of cases is increasing day after day and
called on the humanitarian agencies to distribute chlorine to
shallow wells owners in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen sample tests carried to Nairobi laboratories by
MSF-Spain in north Mogadishu revealed that eight of them were
positive. Martini hospital of south Mogadishu which accommodates
disabled and internally displaced refugees was also reported to
have been hit by the disease. Six people were confirmed suffering
from cholera.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Children Education Fund (UNICEF) is currently
undertaking an anti-cholera campaign by sending health messages
and public awareness program through the local newspapers and
radios.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is also distributing chlorine to the owners of the
shallow wells in Somali capital Mogadishu. More than 500 shallow
wells are currently used in obtaining water by inhabitants of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, women in both sides of the capital have volunteered
to start a garbage collection campaign in the dirty streets of
Mogadishu. They are burning the garbage after collecting them
into trash collection points in a bid to contain the spread of
the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
