<HEADLINE> World Bank to Continue Loans to Macedonia in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has promised to
continue providing loans in 1997 to finance Macedonia's
development in the transport, agricultural, health and social
security sectors.
</P>
<P>
The offer, according to media reports reaching here today, was
made Monday during a meeting between World Bank officials and
Macedonian parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the World Bank has approved loans totaling 270
million U.S. dollars to Macedonia, including 160 million dollars
for helping the government balance its budget and carring out
institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the total are earmarked for developing transport,
agriculture, health and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, both based
in the U.S. capital of Washington, predicted that Macedonia would
need a loan of 85 million dollars this year to support the
development of private sectors. 
</P>
