<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Banks Take to Computerization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Pen-pushing is coming to an end
in major Chinese state-owned commercial banks as the march toward
computers, software and other hi-tech equipment races forward in
an age of electronic gadgets.
</P>
<P>
Four billion yuan was invested in the country's financial
sectors, including the banks, during the Eighth Five-Year Plan
period (1991-1995), according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Some experts estimated that such investments in the Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) could be much higher.
</P>
<P>
China has four large state-owned commercial banks: the
Agricultural Bank of China (ABC), the Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China (ICBC), the China Construction Bank (CCB) and the
Bank of China (BOC).
</P>
<P>
At a recent national financial conference, and the respective
annual meetings of the banks, electronic automation was placed top
of the agenda and listed as one of the major tasks for future
development.
</P>
<P>
Among the four, ABC and CCB have opened their
electronic clearing systems, while the operation in over 80
percent of ICBC's offices having introduced electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
BOC, the leading international banking player in China, has
been comparatively slow in switching to the electronic age,
according to BOC's president Wang Xuebing.
</P>
<P>
He urged relevant departments to make greater efforts to turn
out more applicable software for the bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ICBC, the largest bank in the country, also plans to
concentrate on developing more applicable software. A software
development center was recently set up at the headquarters of the
bank in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said that the great efforts made by the banks on
electronics reflects the increasing sense of commerce and
competition among Chinese commercial banks, which will improve their
performance and risk-prevention abilities and increase their
service.
</P>
<P>
This may further speed up structural reforms to meet the needs
of the market economy and strengthen their viability on the
international and domestic markets, they said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the current electronic efforts of the banks
have created a huge market for high-technology products for the
banking industry.
</P>
<P>
A large number of Chinese and foreign research institutions and
manufacturers have been working to enter the market by
participating in various exhibitions and product presentations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
