<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Union Strikes Resume in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Trade union strikes demanding the
nullification of the new labor law resumed at 20 manufacturing
workplaces in South Korea today, but the fervor of the walkouts
was not as high as expected.
</P>
<P>
The day marked the first occasion of the "Wednesday Strikes" as
announced by the Korea Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU) last
week.
</P>
<P>
Some 34,000 union members went on strike at 20 manufacturing
sites throughout the country today, including Hyundai Motor
Company's Ulsan plant, the Labor Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
However, the KCTU claimed that about 180,000 workers from 170
trade unions went on strike.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the KCTU asked its members to stop strikes on
January 20 and said that it will stage a general strike every
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The strikes began on December 26 last year when the ruling New
Korea Party railroaded the new labor law through the National
Assembly in the absence of opposition legislators.
</P>
<P>
Unionists charge that the new labor law is biased in favor of
management, making it easier for employers to make workers
redundant, extend work hours and recruit replacements for striking
workers.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production losses in South Korea since the start of
the labor strikes have been estimated at 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam met with opposition party leaders Kim
Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil Tuesday and told them that he will
rewrite the controversial labor law and order law enforcement
authorities to suspend executing arrest warrants issued against
trade union leaders who orchestrated the nationwide wildcat
strikes.
</P>
<P>
However, President Kim rejected the opposition leaders' call
for nullifying the new labor law, saying he cannot do something
"unconstitutional." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Returns to Kremlin Amid Lawmakers' Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
returned to the Kremlin this morning amid lawmakers' doubts about
his health.
</P>
<P>
He was earlier expected to stay closeted in his out-of-town
residence for convalescence after double pneumonia for at least
another week.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's arrival for a regular meeting in the Kremlin with
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin came as a surprise to many
people, despite his press secretary's repeated statements that the
president had not cancelled any of his international meetings
scheduled for the end of January and early February.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin underwent a heart bypass surgery on November 5 and was
taken into Moscow's Central Clinical Hospital for double pneumonia
on January 8.
</P>
<P>
After moving from the hospital to a country residence near
Moscow, he had been reportedly working on documents and avoided
meetings with his top officials.
</P>
<P>
Doubts about his ability to regain enough strength to return to
the Kremlin soon were so strong that different sources started to
talk about the "the vacuum of power" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament, even
decided to debate Yeltsin's impeachment on grounds of his ill
health at a meeting today.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the parliament, an item of early
termination of President Yeltsin's powers for health reasons was
put on the agenda of the State Duma plenary meeting this morning.
</P>
<P>
Only 160 legislators opposed the item while 206 voted for it
and two abstained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Breaks Out North of Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
hit back today at its rivals on the front north of the capital of
Kabul, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The fighting erupted outside Charikar, capital of Parwan
Province which lies about 64 kilometers north of Kabul, after jets
belonging to the anti-Taliban alliance bombed the Kabul Airport
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report gave no details about the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militia have achieved a sudden upsurge in fighting
over the past few days when they launched a lightning attack
against the opposition alliance on the front north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The front-line, which a few weeks ago was close to Kabul, has
now been pushed back 100 kilometers into the territory under the
control of the alliance led by Ahmad Masood, commander of the
ousted government forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
