<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Puts Conditions on Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has made its economic
assistance to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
conditional upon more exchanges between the two parts of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Yoo Chong-ha said today Seoul will consider
economic aid if Pyongyang agrees on material and human exchanges
to help build confidence and ease tension on the Korea Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Seoul "cannot accept Pyongyang's demand for food assistance or
economic aid in exchange only for the North (DPRK) taking part in
the proposed four-party talks," Yoo told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Attending the talks involving South Korea, the DPRK, China and
the United States "will not be a sufficient condition for us" to
provide food or any other economic assistance, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, South Korea provided 150,000 tons of
rice and 3 million U.S. dollars in food aid to help ease the
DPRK's severe food shortage caused by devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
Yoo said Seoul will link any further assistance with the DPRK's
efforts to promote confidence-building and ease the tensions.
</P>
<P>
Seoul, he added, will make its position clear at the joint
briefing on the proposed four-party talks to be attended by South
Korea, the DPRK and the United States in New York on January 29.
</P>
<P>
However, Yoo did not rule out the possibility of the South
Korean National Red Cross providing small-scale humanitarian aid
worth several million dollars to the DPRK through international
relief organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
