<HEADLINE> RUF Rebels Trading Along S. Leone-Liberia Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Rebels belonging to the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) are "still engaged" in cross
border trade in farm produce and diamonds along the Sierra
Leone-Liberia border, government guards said today.
</P>
<P>
One of the guards at the boundary, Sulaiman Sesay reached by
phone said, ''they (rebels) are swapping cacao, coffee and gems
with ULIMO-K fighters (one of the factions in Liberia led by
Alhaji Kroma) for arms.''
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for ULIMO-K in Freetown immediately dismissed the
charge as "silly" but residents in the south and eastern border
towns near Liberia have repeatedly complained to government
"about military movements in the area."
</P>
<P>
Last week, a delegation of farmers and sub chiefs sent an
urgent appeal to Sierra Leone's President Tejan Kabbah that a
military outpost should be established in the border if peace is
to be sustained.
</P>
<P>
Travelers have also reported "intensified movements" in the
area and have called for "strong surveillance."
</P>
<P>
Suspicion of strange dealings along the border for sometime round
but these are not viewed as "a threat to the peace process,"
they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
