<HEADLINE> Liberian Faction Pledges Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's Lofa Defense Force
(LDF) has announced plans to disarm all its fighters in the
southwest Saturday amid stepped-up efforts to disarm some 60,000
Liberian factional fighters before the January 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
LDF Chairman Francois Massaquoi said Monday the LDF is ready
to do whatever is necessary to turn in to the West African
peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, all weapons in its
possession before the deadline for voluntary disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"We are anxious to disarm," he said when meeting with ECOMOG
Commander Major-General Victor Malu and his deputy
Brigadier-General Joe Kwateng at the ECOMOG headquarters in
Liberia's capital Monrovia, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Only more than 7,000 fighters have put down their weapons
since the ongoing disarmament operation started on November 22 in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Massaquio said the delay in disarming LDF fighters was due to
some communication difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He said the LDF disarmament in the southwestern Ahmadu town
would be carried out orderly, pledging any LDF fighters who
failed to disarm in accordance with the relevant orders "would
have themselves to blame and should be treated as criminals."
</P>
<P>
In response, Malu said ECOMOG will provide vehicles to
transport LDF fighters to the nearby disarmament sites.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that ECOMOG would not compromise on disarmament
and would be prepared for very efficient military operations
against the fighters who failed to surrender weapons.
</P>
<P>
Malu urged all faction leaders to encourage their fighters to
disarm before the expiration of the January 31 deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
