<HEADLINE> Heavy Debts Put 14,500 Japanese Companies out of Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1996 saw heavy debts
of more than 10 million yen (about 100,000 U.S. dollars) putting
14,544 Japanese companies out of business.
</P>
<P>
Last year was the sixth in a roll that the number of Japanese
businesses filing for bankruptcy surpassed 10,000, according to a
survey by a non-governmental credit rating agency.
</P>
<P>
Survey findings, based on a nationwide study, indicated that
the debt of the bankrupt companies totaled 7.99 trillion yen (69
billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 9,915 manufacturers and financial institutions, or
more than 60 percent of the insolvent businesses, were dragged
down by slow sales and bad loans in the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
