<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pearl River Delta Short of Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Pearl River Delta in
south China, once a favored site for inland laborers, is suffering
from a severe shortage of workers, forcing local firms to cut
production.
</P>
<P>
"For a company, labor is as important as capital, but now it is
difficult to employ skilled workers here," said a Hong Kong
businessman who owns a toy factory in the city of Dongguan.
</P>
<P>
In the early 90's, the area suffered from an influx of farmers
from across the country, who were attracted by the delta's
plentiful job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, many of these farmer-turned-workers,
including some with experience and skill, have returned to their
hometowns.
</P>
<P>
Due to the lack of laborers, many local enterprises have moved
to other parts of the country, said an official with the Foreign
Trade Bureau of Dongguan.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, in addition to the nearly 3.3
million migrants who have been working in local firms, there are
still about three million transient rural laborers in this
area. But the number keeps on shrinking.
</P>
<P>
The number of the non-native laborers in Zhongshan has lowered
from 390,000 to 320,000 over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
A local economist attributes the reduced labor force to the
low-level salaries and the poor welfare conditions for the
employees.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the favorable policies offered by inland
provinces which encourage their natives to invest in their home
places have also contributed measurably to the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Along with the development of China's reform and opening drive,
rural people are able to find job opportunities in many other
parts of the country, according to the economist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aftershocks Happen in Xinjiang Quake-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Two aftershocks measuring 4.5
and 4.1 on the Richter scale have jolted Jiashi and Artux areas in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which were hit
by two earthquakes measuring 6.3 and 6.4 on Richter scale at 9:47
and 9:48 Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
China's State Seismological Bureau cited reports from Xinjiang
Seismological Bureau as saying that the aftershocks happened
between Tuesday morning and 8:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
However, quake experts believe that though a stronger
earthquake is less likely to hit the areas within a short period,
an aftershock measuring over 5 on the Richter scale may still
possibly happen.
</P>
<P>
By 20:50 Tuesday, the two strong quakes had claimed 12 lives,
wounded 40 people, eight of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
The shocks also killed 1,969 cattle, and destroyed 7,300 homes
and eight mosques.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the quake-hit areas currently have trouble in
finding accommodation. Transport and telecommunications are
basically operating normally.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers and armed police have been sent to the quake-hit areas
to help in disaster relief work.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has established a disaster-relief
office to arrange the overall rescue work, and the State
Seismological Bureau and Xinjiang Seismological Bureau have
jointly established an on-the-site work team and rushed to the
quake-hit area.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismological Bureau had earlier predicated that
strong earthquake may happen in Jiashi-Artux area in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
