<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Israel Expects Regional Thaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Encouraged by the positive
reactions from the Arab world and international community to the
recent Hebron troops pullback, Israel is expecting a regional thaw
in Israeli-Arab ties.
</P>
<P>
Following the Hebron redeployment last week, Israel has been
praised for taking a major step toward pushing forward the peace
process by world leaders and notably the moderate Arab gulf and
north African states.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States is making new efforts to build
on the new momentum of the peace process created by the Hebron
deal. It is calling on Arab countries to be more forthcoming
with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, a frequent
target of Arab criticism until recently.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. officials said the Hebron could lead to a regional
thaw that might include a revitalization of the long dormant
multilateral peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Foreign Press Association Tuesday,
U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk made clear that the Arab
states should realize the importance of the Hebron agreement. He
said Arabs should credit Netanyahu for his courage in clinching
and implementing the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. had received signals from Egypt,
Jordan, Morocco and Oman of a willingness to move closer to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
To seize the momentum of Hebron deal, Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy today is expected to brief foreign envoys to
Israel on the Hebron agreement and its smooth implementation.
</P>
<P>
There is speculation here that Netanyahu's foreign policy
adviser Dore Gold will visit a number of Arab countries very
shortly to promote a regional thaw. Top on the agenda will be the
arrangement for Netanyahu's visits to capitals of several major
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told Israel Radio last
week that Cairo would welcome Netanyahu for a visit after the
Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Ambassador Omar Rifai said Tuesday night that
Jordan was now open to a visit by Netanyahu, which could take
place following the end of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan, the
Islamic lunar month, on February 9.
</P>
<P>
Oman Foreign Minister Yusef Ben-Alawi said Tuesday his
country, which has halted normalization with Israel following
Netanyahu's rise to power, was willing to renew its dialogue
with Israel following the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the positive signs created by the Hebron pullback,
a long way still lies ahead for reaching a just, comprehensive
and lasting Israeli-Arab peace.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Palestinian peace track, the immediate
challenges after Hebron deal will be the more complicated and
sensitive final-status talks, which will tackle the fate of
Palestinian territories, Jerusalem and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The central disputes are Israel's opposition to the creation
of an independent Palestinian state with eastern Jerusalem as
capital, which is the long-cherished lofty goal for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The difficulty of Hebron negotiation bode ill for future
talks which are expected to be marked with more deadlocks and
confrontations. And the renewed deadlocks in future talks could
offset any positive effect of the Hebron deal and push the
region back into tension and confrontation.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Syrian track, there is still no sign
indicating that the Hebron deal could help ease the military
tension and restart the long-stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Syria is insisting on Israel's return of whole Golan Heights,
a strategic plateau captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast
War. But the request was flatly rejected by Israel. Without a
solution to the Israeli-Syrian dispute, it will be impossible to
realize a genuine regional thaw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
