<HEADLINE> Israeli, Syrian FMs Exchange Peace Messages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy has exchanged messages with his Syrian counterpart
Farouq Shara on renewing the stalled peace talks, a local
newspaper report said today.
</P>
<P>
Levy and Shara have exchanged views recently through an
European Union minister who acted as a go-between, Hebrew daily
Haaretz reported.
</P>
<P>
The report did not disclose further details about the content
of the messages, which are believed to focus on finding ways to
break the ice in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Until now, there is still no sign of a the quick resumption of
the peace talks between Israel and Syria that have been suspended
since early last year. Because of Israel's objection to returning
the whole Golan Heights, Syria has rejected repeated calls for
resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
The United States is apparently making new efforts to press
for resuming Israeli-Syrian peace track following the recent
Hebron redeployment which has eased tension considerably in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is also keen to play a role in restarting the
Israeli-Syrian peace talks. Shara paid a visit to Cairo recently
in the wake of Israeli pullback in Hebron in an apparent bid to
explore ways of resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an military intelligence report revealed today that
Israel is now viewing Syria as the No. 1 threat to its national
security.
</P>
<P>
An assessment report compiled by Mossad, Israel's secret
military intelligence service, said because the Israeli-Syrian
peace talks are deadlocked, Syria, armed with non-conventional
weapons, is posing a more serious threat than international
terrorism and the dangers of Islamic countries Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The report, published in the front page of the largest Hebrew
daily Yediot Ahronot today, said that the stalemate in the peace
talks would very likely lead to confrontation between Israel and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria is demanding Israel's return of the whole Golan
Heights as a prior condition for resuming the peace talks,
which was turned down by Israeli hardline Likud government.
</P>
</TEXT>
