<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Customs to Enhance IPR Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs is planning
to close shops that are repeatedly prosecuted for selling pirated
materials so as to enhance the protection programs of intellectual
property rights (IPR).
</P>
<P>
According to Lawrence Li Shu-fai, commissioner of Hong Kong
Customs and Excise Department, Hong Kong customs last year added
24 additional posts to its staff to protect intellectual property
rights and a further 24 posts will be created in the future.
</P>
<P>
Li said that in 1996, 477,193 VCDs were seized by the Customs,
compared with 102,654 in the previous year,
</P>
<P>
The customs also seized 330,275 CD-Roms, a rise of 28 percent
over the previous year, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Other counterfeit goods frequently seized included clothes,
leather goods, watches, mobile phone batteries, canned ginseng and
Chinese medicine, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
