<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Meet in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks with Palestinian National Authority(PNA) leader Yasser
Arafat today in their first meeting since PNA took control of most
of the West Bank city of Hebron in a landmark deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to discuss the latest development
of the Mideast peace process and the implementation of the Hebron
deal.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will acquaint Mubarak of the details of the
just-concluded Hebron agreement and raise other issues in the
transitional phase and about the final status in the upcoming
negotiations with Israel, Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zuhdi
al-Qodra told the Egyptian MENA news agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will extend his thanks to Mubarak and the Egyptian
people for their perennial and continuous support and advocacy for
the Palestinian's right, said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here this morning from Rome, where he addressed
a conference of the Socialist International and later had talks
with Prime Minister Romano Prodi and President Oscar Liugi
Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
In Rome, calling for sustained international support for the
Mideast peace process, Arafat said peace is the strategic option
of the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Egypt has said an independent
Palestinian state should be set up to allow the Palestinians to
practice their legitimate right of self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Israeli partial troop withdrawal from the West Bank city of
Hebron was an important step but the Palestinian state should
eventually be declared, said Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will continue its support to the Palestinians till they
establish their own state," he said in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a strong advocate of the Palestinian cause and the
first Arab country to make peace with Israel, has played a pivotal
role in the Palestinian-Israel negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It is behind the proposal which ended last-minute differences
between the Palestinians and Israelis after their months of bitter
wrangling over implementing the Israeli troop redeployment from
Hebron, the last of eight West Bank towns to be handed over to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two sides will resume talks on a
number of other issues immediately after the redeployment and
start talks on a final peace agreement within two months.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader's visit to Egypt comes within the
framework of the frequent coordination between the two leaders. He
is expected to report to the Cairo-based Arab League on the Hebron
agreement and visit other Arab states after the Cairo stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
