<HEADLINE> Iran to Pay 4 Billion Dollar Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran is to pay 4 billion
U.S. dollars of foreign debts that get mature in 1997, local press
reported today, citing banking authorities.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debt payment will constitute 24.89 percent of
the total foreign exchange expenditure, which was approved by
Iran's Parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament voted to approve the ceiling of 16.07
billion dollars for foreign exchange expenditure of the Central
Bank of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen Nourbakhsh, Governor of the Central Bank of Iran,
was quoted by Persian daily Salam as saying that Iran's external
debts total 20 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran is expected to earn a total of 19 billion
dollars of hard currency in 1997, of which 16 billion dollars
will come from oil and gas export, 2.5 to 3 billion dollars from
the exports of non-oil goods.
</P>
<P>
He declared that the foreign exchanged rate would be fixed at
3,000 Iranian rials for one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Since the rescheduling agreements were reached with major
creditors in 1994-95, the repayment of debt has been a top
government priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
