<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Loses 360m Dollars to Foreign Shippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria loses 28.8 billion Naira
(about 360 million U.S. Dollars) a year as indigenous carriers
are not involved in the lifting of crude oil, the country's
number one export item, outside its shores.
</P>
<P>
It will also lose about 216 billion Naira (about 2.7 billion
Dollars) in the next 10 years if indigenous shippers are not
participating in lifting liquefied natural gas.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Alhaji Baba Galadima, director-general
of the National Maritime Authority (NMA), at a meeting with chief
executives of oil companies and related marine service on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government has incurred such huge losses
because indigenous shippers have been kept outside "the lucrative
business" and that all the money due for payment to the NMA
coffers by foreign shippers who lift oil in and out of the
country has not been remitted.
</P>
<P>
"On the average, about a million barrels of crude oil go out
of Nigerian shores per vessel, with each of these being above
500,000 dollars," he said, quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
"No fewer than 60 vessels pass the Nigerian waters monthly.
This is about 360 million Dollars annually. And this is Nigeria's
hard-earned foreign currency. It is not a small amount of money."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the biggest oil producers in west Africa and a member
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, is the only
member of the organization that does not involve indigenous
shippers in the lifting of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
NMA was established after a 1987 decree on national shipping
policy. It has the right to allocate cargoes coming in and going
out of Nigerian waters.
</P>
<P>
Indigenous carriers should be given priority in this respect,
the NMA boss said, but lamenting that some oil companies and
other companies rendering support services to the oil companies
have refused to patronize the indigenous carriers in the
freighting of their cargoes to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Some of the major oil companies, mainly Western companies
operating in Nigeria, have been confirmed to object to
patronizing indigenous shipping companies and this attitude is at
variance of the stipulation of the national shipping policy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the lifting of crude oil and other petroleum
products by indigenous carriers, NMA has begun discussion with
relevant authorities with a view to "involving our national
carriers in this lucrative business," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stated emphatically that NMA has concluded all arrangement
to wage war against the foreign carriers to ensure that
indigenous carriers are involved in the lifting of crude as well
as ensuring that the hard earned foreign currencies do not elude
Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal City Boosts Port Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Trade volume at the ports of
entry in Weihai in east China's Shandong Province has grown at an
annual rate of 93 percent, hitting 3.33 billion US dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
The volumes of cargo, passengers and the number of ships at the
Weihai ports of entry have increased yearly by an average of 82
percent, 65.6 percent and 67.8 percent, respectively, over the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
Weihai has been upgrading its port facilities in recent years
as a result of its flourishing economy stemming from the increase
in port operations. The port presently has 12 berths with an
annual handling capacity of four million tons.
</P>
<P>
Weihai has two Category 1 ports of entry, which are permitted
to handle foreign ships, and three in Category 2. The city has
trade exchanges with more than 30 regions and ports.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate cargo flow through the ports of entry, city
authorities have worked on simplifying customs procedures and
helping foreign-backed companies take full advantage of tax
exemption and other preferential policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
