<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Draft Law on Setting up Islamic Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is drafting
legislation for establishing Islamic banks aimed at encouraging
people to deposit their money in compliance with the Islamic
sharia law.
</P>
<P>
Salem Abdelaziz Al-Sabah, governor of the Central Bank of
Kuwa, said Tuesday that the Kuwaiti market needs these kinds of
banks which applies the Islamic sharia in money dealing, adding
that a certain class of investors might move their funds abroad
if such banks do not exist.
</P>
<P>
He said serious steps are already underway to prepare a bill
on establishing Islamic banks.
</P>
<P>
Islamic banks operate according to rules laid down in Islamic
sharia law that prohibit the payment of interest and investments
in outlawed activities such as brewing or gambling.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has only one Islamic bank, the Kuwait Finance House, where
Muslims can make deposits against seven conventional banks,
although there are several finance institutes that operate
investment funds according to the Islamic code.
</P>
<P>
Islamic banks have become popular among the world's one
billion Muslims, especially in Arab states including the Gulf and
Asian states such as Malaysia and Indonesia, with more than 185
financial institutions. The Islamic financial institutions'
assets had jumped 21 times in 10 years to around 166 billion
U.S. dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti previous parliament had nearly passed a bill on
regulating Islamic bank operations, but the Central Bank called
for drafting an integrated law that takes into account the views
of experts.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah said "a team of technical and legal cadres was
formed at the Central Bank to outline an integrated plan to
prepare the said bill and put it into effect."
</P>
<P>
Adnan Al-Bahar, board Chairman of the International Investor
Company which is run according to the Islamic system, said in an
earlier statement that 1997 would be the year for establishing
Islamic banks.
</P>
<P>
Other Islamic banking institutions operating on the Kuwaiti
market include the International Group, Investment Dar (house)
and International for Murabaha (an Islamic law on resale with
specification of gain). But the Kuwait Finance House remained in
control of the market in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises in East China Seeking Expansion in New Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises in Suzhou, a booming
scenic industrial city in east China's Jiangsu Province,
are seeking expansion in new homes.
</P>
<P>
Seven major industrial enterprises have already moved to the
city's industrial park, where they will spend 230 million yuan on
the renovation of facilities.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises have switched to the industrial park mainly
because of the high-level investment environment and managerial
expertise there, according to officials of the park's managerial
committee.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the enterprises in the park are
foreign-funded. By the end of 1996 the park had brought in 2.5
billion US dollars in foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
The seven enterprises, involved in synthetic crystals,
pesticides, printing, plastics, petrochemicals and automobile
repair, are the first group of domestic enterprises in the
park. They will focus on a number of hi-tech products with
government support. 
</P>
