<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Tops Philippines' Industry Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' infrastructure
sector emerged as the most favored investment area in the country
last year with a project cost of 10.2 billion U.S. dollars, the
Board of Investments (BOI) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Documents from the BOI, the government's investment-licensing
agency, showed that infrastructure accounted for 70.31 percent of
the total approved project cost registered last year.
</P>
<P>
It said that nine big tickets for infrastructure projects
pushed the sector to the number one position, dislodging the
manufacturing sector from the top niche in terms of magnitude of
investments.
</P>
<P>
Next to infrastructure, manufacturing was a distant second
accounting for 9.46 percent of the total project cost.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector garnered 211 projects amounting to
1.38 billion dollars intended in construction, electrical and
electronic products, plastic products, and processed food.
</P>
<P>
In the third place was the public utilities sector with 24
projects valued at 1.37 billion dollars, or almost 9.46 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
Energy-related projects came next, accounting for 3.62 percent
or 526.6 million dollars of the pledged investment total.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors that attracted investments were tourism-oriented
service, mining, and agriculture, the BOI said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
