<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Strengthens Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's opposition
Pan Africanist Congress (PAC) and the Azanian People's
Organization (AZAPO) have agreed to cooperate on a variety of
issues with an aim to have them merged into a single party.
</P>
<P>
A four-member commission, in charge of developing a framework
for PAC-AZAPO cooperation, was formed when the leaders of the two
former liberation movements met here on Tuesday, the Star paper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting "went very well and we left the meeting with lots
of optimism about the future," AZAPO President Mosebudi Mangena
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two parties share the same goals to improve the lives of
the black people and agree in principle to embark on joint
programs on fighting crimes and drugs and preventing the breakup
of black society, Mangena said.
</P>
<P>
PAC Secretary-General Ngila Muendane also expressed optimism
on the merger, saying, "we are going to do everything and
anything together. We are going to protect the victories and
achievements that black communities have made in the past."
</P>
<P>
The PAC and AZAPO, both founded more than 30 years ago, are
among major political parties fighting against apartheid before
1994 non-racial elections.
</P>
<P>
The PAC, which has also agreed to work together with the
Ruling African National Congress, has also held talks with the
Inkatha Freedom Party on possible areas of cooperation, the
report said. 
</P>
