<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Asks Relics Workers to Be Honest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The State Cultural Relics
Bureau urged today that all officials and workers engaged in
relics protection nationwide should carry out their duties
honestly.
</P>
<P>
A new regulation drafted by the bureau states that relics
workers should not take advantage of their position by stealing
and smuggling relics.
</P>
<P>
China issued a regulation in 1981 to monitor relics workers'
morality, but it is outdated and has not always been faithfully
observed.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the bureau said that the adoption of the new
rule will prevent valuable relics from being smuggled, a rampant
occurrence in a country with a 5,000-year-old civilization and
countless unearthed treasures.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates that workers must have a devotion for
relics, and should not pilfer items discovered at excavation sites
and during field investigations.
</P>
<P>
They should keep national secrets, and report relics thievery
in a timely way, according to the new regulation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
