<HEADLINE> 14 Burundi Refugees Buried Alive In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 Burundi
refugees at Kitale Camp in Ngara District of northwestern
Tanzania were buried alive by people with whom they differed
ideologically, the official Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police Sallum George Shabani
was quoted as saying that the killers buried the victims alive in
shallow graves, then lit bonfires on the graves to camouflage
them.
</P>
<P>
Shabani is also in charge of the repatriation of Rwandan and
Burundi refugees starting last month.
</P>
<P>
He said his team had exhumed the bodies of the victims and
re-buried them properly.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 14, only one body was found laid horizontally", he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shabani said the murder has prompted the related authorities
to intensify security in all camps and transfer some of the
refugees from the Kitale Camp.
</P>
<P>
There are about 80,000 Burundi refugees at Kitale and nearby
Lukole camps. They would remain in Tanzania until arrangements
for their safe return to their home country are finalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
