<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Medicare Proposal Well Received </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today put forth a Medicare budget plan which immediately won
praise from congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
The plan would cut the spending of the Medicare, a health
insurance program for the low-income elderly, by 100 billion
U.S. dollars over five years to help balance the budget by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The savings would transfer into 138 billion dollars over six
years, substantially more than the 124 billion dollars Clinton
proposed during budget talks with Congress, which collapsed last
January.
</P>
<P>
Most of the savings would be achieved by reducing payments to
doctors and hospitals. But a portion of it -- 10 billion dollars
over five years -- would come from recipients, by increasing the
premium they would pay for coverage beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Medicare is expected to run out funds by 2001. Clinton has
promised a plan to keep the program solvent for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who was sworn in for his second-term presidency
Monday, met his economic advisers at the White House Tuesday to
discuss a new budget plan.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans, who proposed a cut of 168 billion dollars on
Medicare more than one year ago, spoke warmly about Clinton's new
proposal.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that he has unilaterally moved halfway in our
direction is something that is very, very positive for us," said
Bill Archer, chairman of the Ways and Means Committee of House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
He called it a "tremendous move" but said the Republicans would
have to study the details.
</P>
<P>
House Budget Committee chairman John Kasich said it "brightens
the prospects to get a budget agreement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges Businessmen to Reduce Maize Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
urged millers and traders to reduce their prices and described
the recent price hikes of maize, Zambians' staple food, as
''unjustified''.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, Food and Fisheries Minister Edith Nawakwi said
here on Tuesday that the government may release its maize
reserves on the market if maize traders refuse to reduce the
prices of the staple food immediately, according to Zambia's
Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
She was quoted as saying the increased prices are not
justified and warning that the government will release its maize
stocks, if necessary, to offset the recent hikes, which she said
have been created by a cartel of millers and traders who are
hoarding the commodity in anticipation of a maize shortage this
year.
</P>
<P>
She said her ministry has enough maize stocks to dampen
traders and millers' unjustified prices.
</P>
<P>
In some retail shops in Lusaka, an average of 2,000 Kwacha
(1.5 U.S. Dollars) have been increased on various quantities of
maize with a 25-kilo bag of breakfast meal going at 9,000 to
12,000 Kwacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
