<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Cities Cast Eyes on Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of
profitable companies in economically-developed east China have
shown big interest in China's most-populous Sichuan Province, in
line with the central government's new blueprint for economic
development in central and western China.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan, located in the southwest, has set up firms with the
help of companies in Guangdong, Jiangsu, Fujian, Zhejiang and
Shandong provinces in the form of joint ventures, cooperatives,
mergers, leasing, contracts and share-holding.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, and Sichuan are
jointly building an industrial park at the projected dam area of
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the projects being built in Sichuan are large
and use advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
The Changzhou Diesel Engine Group of Jiangsu Province and its
partner in Sichuan raised 21 million yuan to build a diesel engine
plant with an annual production capacity of 100,000 sets. Its
output will be tripled in three years.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan is rich in energy and cheap labor resources, and
remains under-developed economically, while coastal areas in east
China have adequate operating funds, educated personnel and
up-to-date technology but lack raw materials. Inter-regional
cooperation will help the two sides compensate for each other's
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
The White Cat Group, a noted detergent manufacturer in
Shanghai, purchased a cosmetics plant in Sichuan. The move not
only saved the unprofitable plant but also helped the White Cat
Group to expand its production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
