<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pressure Expected on Syria after Hebron, Lebanon PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri has expected that pressure on Syria and Lebanon to yield
to Israeli conditions will increase following the recent
Israeli-Palestinian agreement on Hebron, Beirut's An-Nahar daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister stressed that he did not anticipate
a Middle East war, because the military option had been tried
by Israel and proved too costly.
</P>
<P>
"Military pressure on Lebanon has proved to be futile,"
Hariri said. "It may kill people, destroy facilities and
terrorize the nation, but in the final result, Lebanon won't
change its political stance."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks during an Iftar, a
breakfast in the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan, which he hosted
Tuesday night for some 1,000 college and university students at
his residence in West Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that Israel was the main beneficiary of "the
no peace, no war status quo" in the region, which, he
noted, is slowing down his government's drive to restore
Lebanon to its pre-civil war glory as the economic center in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that Lebanon does not wish to interfere with
the internal affairs of the Palestinians, but said that the
Hebron agreement was being used by Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu as a propaganda stunt.
</P>
<P>
"Israel is trying to polish its image abroad, and the
Western media are trying to market Netanyahu's government as a
peace-loving body as if Netanyahu has taken an important step
toward peace when in fact what is happening is contrary to
that," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that what Netanyahu signed was "an agreement
which had been concluded by the previous Labor government
which he tried to circumvent for six months to delay a
redeployment form Hebron."
</P>
<P>
"This only proves the lack of seriousness on the Israeli
side to achieve peace," the Lebanese prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Israeli forces last week handed 80
percent of Hebron to the Palestinian Authority led by Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
As to the impact of the agreement on Lebanon, Hariri said
Israel and its Western allies were likely to exert more pressure
on Syria and Lebanon until "one day we'll give in and say 'fine,
let's finish with it and sign a deal irrespective of the
conditions."
</P>
<P>
He vowed that his government will never bow to this pressure
"because such a deal would spark divisions in the country."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, resisting pressure is necessary so that
the peace will be achieved only after the Lebanese conditions
are met.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon demands a full implementation of U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425, which calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
