<HEADLINE> First Foreign-Funded Road for Fuzhou City Proper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Fuzhou, capital of east China's
Fujian Province, is building its first ever foreign-funded road
within the city.
</P>
<P>
The new road will stretch from Wusibei Road in the south, pass
over Dongpu Road, the Waifu rail line, the third beltway, and
Jin'an River, and reach the crossing of Zhanban Road and Pudang
Road, with a total length of about five kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The project, being undertaken by a Japanese company in
cooperation with Chinese companies, will be completed in 18
months, at a total cost of about 200 million yuan (24.1 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local authorities say the 42-meter-wide road will become a
trunk highway in the urban area of Fuzhou, and greatly ease the
traffic conditions in the city's northern part. A large tract of
land alongside the road will also be developed, creating more
space for urban development.  
</P>
