<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yuan Under Appreciation Pressures (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese currency is under
pressure to appreciate further this year, but the country's
central bank will not let it rise all the way, according to
officials and experts.
</P>
<P>
"This year the yuan will remain strong against the US dollar as
the supply of foreign exchange will continue to exceed demand," a
senior official of the State Administration of Foreign Exchange
(SAFE) told Xinhua News Agency recently.
</P>
<P>
The supply of hard currencies has outgrown demand since China
overhauled its foreign exchange system in January 1994 by
devaluing the yuan from 5.7 against the greenback to 8.7, thereby
unifying the currency's dual exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The yuan has since strengthened to around 8.3 against the US
dollar. It gained nearly 0.3 percent over the greenback in 1996,
following a rise of 1.5 percent and 2.9 percent, respectively, in
1995 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
"All the measurable factors foretell the further expansion of
our reserves and an oversupply of foreign exchange, leaving the
yuan under pressure to gain more ground," the SAFE official said.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves have grown significantly in
recent years, to 105 billion US dollars at the end of last year
from merely 21.3 billion US dollars at the year-end of 1993.
</P>
<P>
The official explained that this year China is again expected
to post a trade surplus, which stood at 12.2 billion US dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
The rising momentum of foreign direct investment in China,
which reached more than 41 billion US dollars in 1996, will remain
strong thanks to an improving investment environment and good
economic prospects.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the People's Bank of China (PBC) will
not let the yuan go up all the way and also dismissed the
possibility that the central bank will bow to pressures from
exporters to artificially depress the local currency.
</P>
<P>
"If the central bank can buy foreign exchange at a cheaper
price, why should it pay a higher price?" the official
asked. "Exporters should improve their competitiveness through
their own efforts."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Develops Non-Traditional Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia earned 1.7 billion
Kwacha (1.3 million U.S. Dollars) from non-traditional exports to
Nordic countries in 1996, Commerce, Trade and Industry Deputy
Minister Ackim Nkole said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's non-traditional exporting items include live fish,
game trophies, handcrafts, coffee and particle boards, Nkole said
at a one-day exporters seminar on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In view of the continuous decline and the ever fluctuating
prices for metal products on the world market, non-traditional
exports are the only alternative to economic recovery in the
copper-rich country, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's non-traditional exports, particularly agriculture and
forestry products, are renewable and competitive on world markets
for years as long as better methods of production are applied, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government and the Export Board of Zambia are currently
mobilizing technical and financial assistance from donor agencies
to support exporters who facing problems on sourcing cheaper
pre-shipment and finance, Nkole added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yuan Under Appreciation Pressures (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tao Liming, deputy director of the International Finance
Research Institute under the Bank of China, said that the local
currency will continue to be in short supply as China is keeping a
moderately tight monetary policy this year.
</P>
<P>
"The yuan will remain solid unless basic construction overheats
and imports run out of control," he said, noting that the two will
not happen this year as the central government has vowed
repeatedly to pursue stable economic growth and cut inflation
further to embrace the resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong
and the convocation of the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the forces pushing up the value of the local currency
still exist this year and I don't see any signs for it to
depreciate in a foreseeable time frame," Tao said, adding that he
expects China's foreign exchange reserves to grow by around 20
billion US dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Tao said that the firmness of the yuan indicates a sound macro
economy but adversely affects some micro economic aspects, such as
dampening exports.
</P>
<P>
"And I have to say the double-edged exchange rate is inevitable
in a market economy, and the reality is that we are developing a
market economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the central bank will continue to purchase
hard currencies, though a rapidly-expanding foreign exchange
reserve, which increases money supply, has been partly blamed for
inflationary pressures in past years.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way for the central bank to avoid the bad effects
of a consolidating exchange rate and an enormous foreign exchange
reserve at the same time," Tao pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"From a realistic point of view, the PBC will opt for a
relatively stable exchange rate of the yuan and let the currency
reserves grow," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, a second SAFE official told Xinhua that it could be
harmful if China too heavily emphasizes the stability of the
yuan's exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"The market will decide the value of the yuan," he said. "Why
should we let overseas speculators take advantage of our promise
to keep it stable?"
</P>
<P>
Tang Jiying, vice president of the Shanghai-based China Foreign
Exchange Trade System, said that the yuan's current exchange rate
basically reflects its value.
</P>
<P>
The yuan was quoted today at 8.2955 against the US currency, up
from 8.3174 in early 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Changes Give Rise to Higher Divorce Rate in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China's rising divorce rate is
the result of overwhelming social changes brought on by the
country's reform and opening up, a recent survey by the
Procurators Daily shows.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey of 100 divorce cases handled by a local
court since 1992, 18 percent of those who initiated divorce
proceedings are newly-promoted officials from the government and
state-owned enterprises. Seven percent of them are women.
</P>
<P>
The increase is three times higher than that before 1992, it
says.
</P>
<P>
China's divorce rate has climbed from 5.9 per thousand in 1990
to 7.1 per thousand in 1995. And the rate is expected to be much
higher in 1996, an official with the Civil Affairs Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The opportunity to change jobs, which was difficult under the
former planned economic structure, has prompted more divorces in
recent years, the survey says.
</P>
<P>
It explains that many who left government institutions and
state-owned enterprises for more profitable private or foreign
funded businesses have decided they and their spouses are no
longer compatible.
</P>
<P>
Also increasing are divorces that allow either spouse to evade
debts or for women to have more children, thereby bypassing the
state family planning policy.
</P>
<P>
Second divorces, which have only become frequent in recent
years, have also increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
