<HEADLINE> Rwanda Varsity Seeking Coop With Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Chancellor of the National
University of Rwanda (UNR) Deo Kambanda has encouraged more
south-to-south cooperation among African countries rather than
perpetual dependence on western countries.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda, who is on a two-day visit to Zimbabwean universities
before proceeding to other southern African universities to
discuss cooperation pacts, said Africa had enough professional
manpower to develop the continent.
</P>
<P>
''We have brilliant brains here. Why can't we use them,'' he
asked after a tour of the National University of Science and
Technology (NUST) in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest city on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Kambanda would discuss exchange programs for
Rwandan and southern African university students and lecturers.
</P>
<P>
He said currently his university has about 4,000 students and
the intake would be increased to 6,000 next year.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda described the situation in Rwanda as ''99 percent
normal''. ''There is no more conflict between tribes. The main
problem at the moment is re-integrating returning refugees,'' he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
