<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia Thinks Big for Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Many Malaysians appear
modest in their vision of a modernized country compared with their
prime minister who has vowed to catapult the nation to "the full
promise of the Information Age" by 2020.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has successfully transformed its agriculture-based
economy to an industrial one which grew at a rapid rate of eight
percent annually for the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, aiming much higher,
said that the progress of the nation would be stalled unless it
joins the emerging new industries of the Information Age in a
world which is leaving the Industrial Age behind.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir returned here today after a 10-day working visit to
the United States and Japan, where he expounded emphatically and
eloquently his country's drive to modify its strategy to move
towards the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
Although Malaysia's economic prospects are bright with a high
growth rate of 8-8.3 percent in reach this year, challenges remain
to overcome lower competitiveness and structural weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
The country's competitiveness is affected by wage increases
that outpace productivity growth, a low level of research and
development activities, and little innovative capability.
</P>
<P>
To improve its competitiveness, Malaysia is shifting to
capital- intensive and high-tech-intensive investments for the
future sustainable economy, in which services will be the biggest
sector, ahead of manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's trip to the U.S. and Japan was specially intended
for promoting Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), a
multi-billion-dollar high-tech project, and for seeking help from
world-renowned hardware and software companies to develop the
country's multimedia industries.
</P>
<P>
"We can't ignore developments in the field of Information
Technology (IT)," Mahathir said,
</P>
<P>
He noted that unless Malaysians actively take part in the
Information Age activities, they would lag behind in their way of
life and even their intellectual growth.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the country's future will see the creation
of an environment where the IT industry will form the backbone of
a new way of life, while for Malaysians, exciting times are ahead
as they learn to adapt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia Thinks Big for Future (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The MSC, covering a zone of 15 kilometers by 50 kilometers
south of Kuala Lumpur, is designed to offer a prefect environment
for companies wanting to develop and distribute multimedia
products and services.
</P>
<P>
During the trip to the U.S. and Japan, Mahathir drummed up
support for the development of the MSC, a brainchild of his own,
which he said would serve as a launching pad for the IT
transformation of an entire nation and a gateway to a dynamic and
prosperous future.
</P>
<P>
The response he received for the upcoming MSC development has
been most positive, especially as support is coming from the
world's leading high-technology companies in multimedia and
knowledge-based industries.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 American companies, including Microsoft
Corporation, have shown interest in investing in the MSC and a
number of Japanese companies, including Japanese giant Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corporation (NTT), also indicated their
keenness to invest in the MSC.
</P>
<P>
In addition to political stability and economical
competitiveness, Malaysia has promised attractive incentives to
potential investors, such as no taxes, no investment allowance tax
for the first decade of operating and no duties on multimedia
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The country is also drawing up a set of cyberlaws including
those on computer crime, intellectual property rights and digital
signature to protect investors in the MSC.
</P>
<P>
Chief executives of the companies who showed very strong
support for the project "find that the conditions, the laws, the
policies as well as the practices in the MSC are conducive to
their participation," said Mahathir, who had meetings with them.
</P>
<P>
To kick-start the MSC, Malaysia identified seven specific
flagship applications for development in the first phase, which
are electronic government, smart schools, telemedicine, research
and development clusters, the national multipurpose card,
worldwide manufacturing webs and borderless market centers.
</P>
<P>
As envisaged by Mahathir, the second phase will involve linking
the MSC with other islands of excellence of the country and phase
three will see the whole of Malaysia leapfrogging into the
Information Age with the entire country "living and working in
these new ways."
</P>
<P>
"I fully expect that this 'web' will extend beyond Malaysia's
borders and out across Malaysia's multicultural links to our
neighbors," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the MSC would eventually become a
global bridge when its web is linked to those of other regions in
the world.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the MSC, a network of world-class and
local companies will hopefully be enlisted to help Malaysia
achieve the goals of its Vision 2020, which is to attain the
status of a developed country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
