<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Supporters Just Fantastic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Soccer has brought a legendary
fame to the northern seaport city of Dalian, Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The most prosperous city in Liaoning Province enjoys a
reputation as a "green city" as well as a "soccer capital."
</P>
<P>
Dalianers still talk about the stunning performance by their
favorite (Dalian) Wanda team in 1996, a season when the side did
not lose a single game, netting their second Chinese professional
league title.
</P>
<P>
Every Dalian family has at least one soccer fan. But the fans
among nearly two million urban residents used to revel in untamed
enthusiasm in their soccer stadium, regardless of whether their
team won or hit a losing streak.
</P>
<P>
Then people came to realize that the sports stadium was an
instant showroom of their city, especially in a place where the
residents took pride in their sporting traditions.
</P>
<P>
Soccer fans in Dalian set up an association to produce its own
pennant, badge and mascot.
</P>
<P>
"Spirited enthusiasm should not be outlawed on the soccer
field," Zhang Jiashu, the secretary general of the association,
said, "however, being energetic but not rude is a golden rule for
our fans."
</P>
<P>
Fans rallied in the downtown sports stadium to celebrate and
rally every week in the last 11-week season. Confetti, trumpets
and military bands showed their enthusiasm in a colorful way,
replacing the old style of throwing soda bottles and hurtling foul
words.
</P>
<P>
Warm support to the fans added fuel to the team's performance
and instilled a sense of pride among the city's soccer
professionals.
</P>
<P>
"We really show our gratitude to such warm and polite fans,"
said Wang Jianlin, chairman of the Wanda Group, a
major sponsor of Dalian's soccer team, citing that his team's
record of never losing a home game in three years has been a
victory for all fans.
</P>
<P>
A package tour by 300 fans to Beijing for an away-game last
year gave the Dalian supporters a chance to show Beijingers their
good manners and expertise in watching soccer games.
</P>
<P>
Team manager Chi Shangbin even bowed in thanks that night
to the stand holding Dalian fans. He wanted to thank them
personally - in full view of the country's capital - for their
politeness and support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
