<HEADLINE> 22,000 Burundi Refugees Flee To Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- About 22,000 Burundi
refugees have fled their country for neighboring Tanzania and the
pace of their exodus is picking up, the U.N. refugee agency said.
</P>
<P>
Pamela O'Toole, spokesman of the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR), said here on Tuesday that more refugees are
fleeing the fighting in southwestern Burundi to join 134,,000
displaced Burundians who escaped to Tanzania in November and
December.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 Burundi Hutus have been forced out of eastern
Zarie by an ethnic Tutsi rebellion.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR Commissioner Sadako Ogata will visit Burundi, Zaire,
Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda from February 6 to 15.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR charged that hundreds of returnees have been killed
by Burundi's Tutsis-dominated army since the minority Tutsis
seized power in a military coup on July 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
In the latest reported massacre earlier this month, Burundi
troops killed 126 Hutu returnees expelled from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
A total of some 150,000 people have been killed in the tiny
central African country during a three-year war between the army
and Hutu rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
