<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land in China's Fujian under Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
dealt with 65 cases of illegal land use over the past two years as
part of a province-wide land protection campaign.
</P>
<P>
More than 21 unauthorized structures built on cultivated land
have been pulled down, and 47 hectares of land reclaimed.
</P>
<P>
Fujian is one of the Chinese provinces that suffer from an
acute shortage of cultivated land, with only 0.038 hectares per
person.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure adequate grain supplies, the province has
adopted a series of financial and legal regulations and invested
20 million yuan (about 2.4 million US dollars) to place 82 percent
of the farmland under top protection.
</P>
<P>
Developers who want to use land are required to obtain a permit
and pay high compensation costs. And officials' performance is
linked with their efforts to curb the shrinking land space.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than one million hectares of basic farmland
have been effectively saved.
</P>
<P>
To meet the demand for land development, the province has set
aside 3,300 ha of idle land for construction of towns and
villages, foreign-backed projects, and industrial zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
