<HEADLINE> China's Chemical Export Sets Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI (Shandong), January 22 (Xinhua) -- China set a record in
its import and export of chemical products in 1996, with the
annual value topping 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The export increased by a big margin, hitting 12 billion U.S.
dollars last year, said Gu Xiulian, Chinese minister of the
chemical industry, at a national conference held recently in
Weihai, a port city in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
An outstanding characteristic in chemical development last year
was the big rise in the long and medium-term investment from
abroad, Gu said.
</P>
<P>
Many large foreign corporations have been involved in the
development of some key chemical works by setting up holding
companies in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese chemical giants have extended their market
absorption, selling complete sets of equipment and exporting
laborers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China held an international chemical exhibition
which attracted 1,800 domestic and foreign chemical works and
snatched a transaction value of 12 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Outlining tasks for this year, Gu said chemical industry should
raise efficiency and improve product quality, explore more new
markets, develop technology-intensive and value-added products and
enhance cooperation with other countries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, China is to export 20 billion U.S.
dollars-worth of chemicals and absorb 12 billion US dollars of
foreign investment a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
