<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaigning By-Elections Ends in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Campaigning activities for
the lower house of parliament by-elections in Nepal ended last
night as voting was only two days away, election officials said
today.
</P>
<P>
Under the election code of conduct, candidates and their
supporters are prohibited from taking out processions, raising
slogans or carrying out any campaigning activities 48 hours before
the voting day.
</P>
<P>
The by-elections, scheduled for Friday, will be held at five
constituencies throughout the country to fill the five vacant
seats of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
A total of 46 candidates including 25 independents have
registered for the by-elections, according to the Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Major political parties including the main ruling Nepali
Congress (NC) and the main opposition Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) have fielded their candidates
at each of the five constituencies in districts of Kathmandu,
Sunsari, Rupandehi, Baitadi, and Rautahat.
</P>
<P>
The NC, which has 86 MPs in the 205-seat lower house, has vowed
to win all the five seats in order to replace the CPN-UML as the
single largest party in parliament. The CPN-UML at present holds
87 seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
Only one woman candidate, who represents the National
Democratic Party (RPP), the second largest party in the NC-led
three-party ruling coalition, will run for the by-election at the
Kathmandu constituency.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has introduced a voter's identity card
system on an experimental basis in the by-elections at the
Kathmandu, Sunsari and Baitadi constituencies, Commission
officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
