<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Found in Malaysia-Thailand Joint Development Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysia-Thailand
Joint Authority (MTJA) today confirmed that gas has been
discovered in the Muda Field of their Joint Development Area (JDA)
after successful drilling and testing of the Muda-3 appraisal well
by the contractors.
</P>
<P>
The Muda-3 well has been drilled to a depth of 2,944 meters.
Gas finds were confirmed over the field located some 272
kilometers east of Thailand's Songkhla and 178 kilometers
northwest of Malaysia's Kota Bharu, it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Four drill stem tests yielded a combined stable gas flow rate
of 22 million standard cubic feet per day and 259 barrels per day
of condensate, it added.
</P>
<P>
MTJA is a statuary body vested with the exclusive rights,
power, liberties and privileges of exploring and exploiting
petroleum resources in the JDA under the MTJA Acts 1990 of
Malaysia and Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Parties Hang on Financial Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The three parties of Bosnia
have failed to reach agreement on the issues of setting up an
integrated central bank and using the same currency in the
country, said a senior bank official in Sarajevo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
K. Omicevic, president of the National Bank of Bosnia and
Herzegovina, said that during the negotiations among the
representatives from the three parties, the Serbs insisted on
establishing their own central bank and currency, which was turned
down by representatives from the Muslem-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bosnian constitution and the Dayton peace
agreements, which were signed in December 1995 ending the
three-and-half year Bosnian War, there should be one central bank
and one single currency in the country.
</P>
<P>
The international community has also required Bosnia to set up
an integrated central bank before it provides financial aid to the
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Bosnian Serbs, Muslems and Croats have their own
respective central banks and currencies, and they are negotiating
on the issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
