<HEADLINE> U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Visits Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott today flew to Moscow to prepare for a
U.S.-Russia summit in March.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin planned to meet in March assuming Yeltsin's health is up
to it.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, accompanied by Gore's chief foreign policy adviser,
Leon Fuerth, is also making arrangements for a visit here in two
weeks by Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
The issue of NATO's enlargement, which is opposed by Russia,
will be high on the agenda of Talbott's vist.
</P>
<P>
Talbott's departure leaves a vacancy in the U.S. Secretary
of State's office. He was designated as the Secretary of State,
Ad Interim as the terms of Warren Christopher ended
officially on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Christopher's successor, Madeleine Albright, is expected to be
confirmed as the Secretary of State by the Senate later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
