<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Private Sector to Start Commodity Futures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will soon have its
first commodity futures market managed by the private sector,
according to official sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Like the stock market, the futures trading will be entrusted to
private business, while the government will merely act as
supervisor, Industry and Trade Minister Tungky Ariwibowo told a
house plenum here Tuesday when submitting to parliament the bill
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The plan will be immediately set in motion after its bill has
been enacted by the House of Representatives," said Tungky.
</P>
<P>
Commodity futures trading has been in operation in Indonesia,
but only as an extension of overseas markets such as the Tokyo
Commodity Futures and the Malaysia Commodity Stock Exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Tungky said that the Indonesian government has drawn up
guidelines for the implementation of the bill and provided
intensive training for department personnel and bourse
participants.
</P>
<P>
Basically, the exchange was designed to achieve social welfare,
ensure efficient and effective trade, and keep out speculators.
</P>
<P>
"This exchange is also another bid to improve the efficiency
and competitiveness of Indonesia's non oil/gas exports," Tungky
added.
</P>
<P>
Commodities most likely to be traded initially include rubber
and coffee futures, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
