<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's total savings deposits increased by
8.5 billion pesos (1 peso equals nearly 1 U.S. dollar) between
October 1995 and October 1996, rising from 45.98 billion to
53.597 billion.
</P>
<P>
According to an analysis released by the central bank, the
growth of private bank deposits was most outstanding, whose
deposits constituted 33.5 percent of the total in October 1995 and
39 percent in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- During the last two months of 1996, Uruguayan
wool exports soared by 44.4 percent compared with the same period
of the previous year, reaching about 21,400 tons.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's wool secretariat said the exports revenues went up
from 67 U.S. million in October and November 1995 to 72 million
during the same months in 1996.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's Agriculture Ministry has issued a new
decree that rules out the purchase of overseas wines that contain
additives or pollutants banned by Brazilian legislation.
</P>
<P>
The decree will become effective on May 16 this year.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- In 1996, private investment in Nicaragua grew by
20.2 percent while public investment decreased by 5.6 percent,
according to the Economy and Development Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Private investment totaled 281 million dollars in 1996, of
which 85 million dollars came from foreign investment. Meanwhile
public investment was 290 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's Chemical and Mining Society (SQM), a
company monopolizing the production and exportation of several
nonmetallic minerals including iodine, has prescribed that it will
export 140 million dollars worth of iodine this year, double the
number of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Encinas, the general manager of the SQM's iodine
division, said that his company is currently supplying 30 percent
of the global iodine demand and boasts of a production of more
than 6,000 tons every year.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Banana exports of Costa Rica fell by 3.46 percent
in 1996 compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Costa Rica exported 105
million boxes of bananas (each weighs 18 kilograms) in 1996, worth
of 600 million U.S. dollars against 1995's 620.77 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural authorities attributed the fall to natural
disasters and high costs of banana production.
</P>
<P>
At present banana-growing activities provide the country with
more than 40,000 jobs and benefit another 100,000 people
indirectly. The average salaries earned by banana workers are the
highest in this country's farm sector.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia drilled 22 oil wells in 1996,
according to Ecopetrol, Colombia's state-owned petroleum company.
Ten wells turned out productive and eight were dry, pending the
results of the remaining four. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
