<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Troops Continue to Shell Muslim Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops
continued to shell the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels
in southern Philippines, sending hundreds of residents to flee,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Al-Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs, said the
military was still conducting ground-to-ground and aerial
bombardment in Buldon, the main camp of the rebel group in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
About 300 families have already fled the area and a "massive
evacuation" is going on, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the military said that the evacuation was "very
minimal" and the residents began to return to their homes as the
situation has been put under control.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Army's Sixth
Infantry Division surrounding the MILF stronghold, admitted that
there was shelling, but described it as "necessary" to protect the
residents from lawless elements.
</P>
<P>
The MILF warned that there was "a very high probability" that
it would back out of the peace talks with the government if the
military presence and armed conflicts continue in the area.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway group of the Moro National Liberation
Front that signed a peace agreement with the government last
September, is growing into the biggest rebel group in the country.
</P>
<P>
The joint technical committee of the government and the MILF
discussed the guidelines and framework for their future formal
peace talks at their first meeting on January 7-8. They are
scheduled to meet again on February 25-26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
