<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Make Efforts to Develop Ties With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine would make great efforts
to develop the relations with Russia and no one could hamper the
process, Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko said today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, Udovenko said Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov's
remarks on Sevastopol should not negatively affect the existing
ties and their development prospects between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, during his visit to Sevastopol in Crimean
peninsula which is the home port of the Black Sea Fleet, Luzhkov
declared that Sevastopol was and is a city of Russia. On Sunday
Ukraine lodged a protest, warning that the mayor's statements
could affect Ukrainian-Russian relations and bring about their
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Russians account for about 70 percent of the population of
Sevastopol, and are in the majority across Crimea which was
Russian territory until 1954 when the then Soviet leader Nikita
Khrushchev gave it to Ukriane in a symbolic gesture of friendship.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine have been fighting over the city since the
Soviet collapse in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko told reporters today that he had written to Luzhkov
not to go to Sevastopol, but he still went there and Ukraine took
a "tolerant attitude" to the issue. He said Luzhkov's remarks were
"very rude" and "unacceptable" to his country.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine condemned Luzhkov's remarks, but it would never take
his remarks as the basis of establishing the ties with Russia,
Udovenko stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine expected Russian President Boris Yeltsin to
recover from his illness as early as possible and resume
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
