<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Continues Search for Missing Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's air force with
assistance from the navy continued its search for the third day
for the missing Y-12 aircraft with a crew of four off the northern
coast, military sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, which took off at the Palaly base on a
reconnaissance mission Monday, might have been gunned down by
Tamil rebels, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The loss of the Y-12 aircraft came six days after the
disappearance of an Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) of the Sri
Lankan Air Force over Pooneryn in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-built UAV, acquired last year, vanished during a
surveillance mission. Attempts to locate it have so far failed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the air force lost another aircraft last evening
when a multi-role Israeli-built Kfir fighter on a bombing mission
crashed into the Nogombo lagoon, over 30 kilometers north of
Colombo, shortly after take-off. The pilot ejected and landed
safely a few kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
Since the resumption of fighting between the Tamil rebels and
government forces in April 1995, the air force has lost 11
aircraft including helicopters.
</P>
<P>
At least 300 persons were killed in these incidents, according
to local press reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
