<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Malaysia to Hold Talks on Dispute Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Malaysia are
preparing to hold another round of talks to settle their dispute
over the Ligitan and Sipadan islands after completing the first
round early this month, a Foreign Ministry official said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Izhar Ibrahim, director general for political affairs of the
ministry said last night the preparations were being made although
it was still not certain when the second round of talks would take
place.
</P>
<P>
The two countries at a meeting between President Soeharto and
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammed in Kuala Lumpur last October
agreed to submit their dispute to the International Court of
Justice (ICJ) in the Hague and their subsequent talks concerned
the processes and procedures they would follow in seeking the
arbitration, Ibrahim said.
</P>
<P>
In their talks held early this month, the two sides agreed to
meet again in Jakarta but "so far there is no certainty yet as to
when the second round of talks will be held because consultations
on it are still going on at departmental level," he said
</P>
<P>
Sipadan and Ligitan are small islands located in the Makassar
strait on the sea border between the Indonesian province of East
Kalimantan and the eastern Malaysian state of Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The dispute surfaced in 1969 when the two sides were engaged in
efforts to delineate their continental shelves. Since then the two
sides twice attempted to settle their overlapping claims to the
islands in bilateral talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
