<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Puts New Airport Project on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The cabinet of Thailand has put
the second Bangkok international airport project, also known as
the Nong Ngu Hao airport, on indefinite hold.
</P>
<P>
At the cabinet meeting on Tuesday, most cabinet ministers
supported Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's proposal to
shelve the project, conceived 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Delays to design work on the new airport terminal and the
relocation of local people had already left the first phase three
years behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said the first phase of the new airport could not be
completed by the year 2000 as scheduled and continuation would run
against the austerity policy of the government.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is facing a current account deficit and the government
has adopted a policy to cut spending on huge projects which do not
have top priority.
</P>
<P>
The state has already spent 6 billion baht (240 million US
dollars) on the project, which is just outside southeast Bangkok
in Samut Prakan province.
</P>
<P>
The project site is low-lying and flood-prone, needing refill
with sand, subsequently raising the cost.
</P>
<P>
To cope with increased passenger volume over the next 10 years,
Chavalit suggested that the air force base adjacent to the
existing Bangkok Don Muang International Airport, be given over to
civil use and the air base be relocated.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of Don Muang airport would cost 10 billion baht
(about 400 million dollars), while implementation of the first
phase of Nong Ngu Hao alone would require 97 billion baht (3.88
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the high-speed train between Bangkok and the eastern
province of Rayong is likely to be derailed by the scrapping of
Nong Ngu Hao airport.
</P>
<P>
Without a connection to the airport, the 190-km rail link would
not be viable, a transport and communications official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
