<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic, Germany Declare Post-War Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Czech Prime Minister Vaclav
Klaus and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl signed here today a joint
declaration of reconciliation between the Czech Republic and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Germany confessed its historical
responsibility for the Second World War, expressed its sorrow for
the 1938-45 Nazi occupation of the Czech lands and asked the Czech
people for "forgiveness".
</P>
<P>
Prague expressed its regret for its expulsion of 2.5 million
Sudeten Germans and the confiscation of their property after the
war.
</P>
<P>
The accord also included Germany's support for the Czech
Republic's efforts to obtain membership of the European Union and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
"The declaration which we have just signed is a big step
forward for both of our nations," Kohl said after the signing of
the declaration at Prague's Liechtenstein Palace.
</P>
<P>
The accord will mean better neighborly relations and peaceful
co-existence in Europe, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to set up a 160 million mark
(98.6 million U.S. dollars) "Future Fund".
</P>
<P>
Most of the money will come from Germany and is primarily
intended to benefit victims of the Nazi aggression.
</P>
<P>
The accord, drawn up after two years of delicate talks, is
opposed by the Czech Republic's Republicans, who won 18 of the 200
seats in parliamentary elections last June, and the Communists,
who won 22.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans staged a demonstration today and referred the
accord to the 1938 Munich Agreement which ceded the Sudetenland,
then part of Czechoslovakia, to Germany and the communists say the
declaration is a threat to Czech sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
