<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 30 Million People Live in Absolute Poverty in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of people
living in abject poverty in Brazil is 30.4 million, 20 percent of
the country's population. The number has dropped by 13 million in
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The abject poverty population is predominately urban in the
nineties, while in the sixties it was a rural-dominated poverty
population, according to a study by the Getulio Vargas Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Of the total population living in poverty, 23.1 million are
concentrated in the cities, nine million live in the big cities,
2.6 million live in the metropolitan region of Sao Paulo, 2.1
million in Rio de Janeiro and 7.3 million in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
About 13.5 million, 44.31 percent of the country's 30.4 million
poor people concentrate in northeastern Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
