<HEADLINE> Nationwide Anti-Fraud Crackdown Generates Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China will continue the cleanup
and standardization of consumer good market this year by
tightening inspection of quality of products in large and
medium-sized department stores.
</P>
<P>
The medium-sized shops, with an annual sales volume of more
than 50 million (six million US dollars), is part of the country's
anti-fraud drive this year, a report in "China Daily" quoted an
official in charge of quality control as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Technical Supervision (SBTS) and the
Ministry of Internal Trade early last year launched a nationwide
crackdown to clean up the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Large state-owned department stores and more than 400 shopping
centers, each of which boasts an annual sales volume of 100
million yuan (12 million US dollars), were the first to be
examined, said Ye Bolin with the SBTS.
</P>
<P>
The inspections, first conducted by the shops themselves and
then by local authorities in charge of technical supervision and
commercial administration, focused on packaged food, clothes,
leather goods, chemical products for daily use, cosmetics, gold
and jade ornaments and electric house appliances.
</P>
<P>
"Regional results indicate large state-owned department stores
are trustworthy regarding the quality of goods and services," Ye
said.
</P>
<P>
"Though complete information about the results of this cleanup
crackdown is still not available, the move has helped strengthen
management of markets, improve the quality commodities and of the
people who work in the sector and protect the legal rights of
consumers," said Wang Qing, an official with the Ministry of
Internal Trade.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned department stores have served for decades as
the main channel of commodity distribution in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
