<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Praises Mercosur, Criticizes Helms-Burton Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President
James Carter today described the South American Common Market
(Mercosur) as "a marvelous development" for the region.
</P>
<P>
Carter, who arrived in Buenos Aires Sunday on a Latin American
tour, also criticized the Helms-Burton Act as a "serious error or
disaster".
</P>
<P>
Carter said at a news briefing that Mercosur not only helped to
lower trade barriers and increase trade but served as a way to
achieve harmony and cooperation between its member states.
</P>
<P>
It also helped to boost citizen exchanges and prevent political
tensions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Carter criticized the United States' position on Cuba. He said
the Helms-Burton Act was "a trade embargo that severely punishes
the people of Cuba and hinders a peaceful resolution to the
differences between the United States and Cuba."
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. president also mentioned the Malvina (Falkland)
Islands issue and said the United States might agree to mediate
between Argentina and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Malvina Islands (also called Falkland Islands), located to
the east of Argentina in the Atlantic, is a former colony of
Britain. Both countries have claimed sovereignty over the islands
with no agreement reached so far. In 1982, Britain fought a war
with Argentina over the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Carter said that the U.S. government would keep neutral and it
wished for a resolution to the issue satisfactory to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Carter made his Latin American tour to advance political
consultations in order to organize the theme of the Latin American
Conference to be held in the U.S. in April.
</P>
<P>
Carter's next stops will be Brazil and Jamaica. He has been to
Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Administration of Cultural Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Culture
announced today that it will improve its management over the
cultural market in 1997, trying every strategy it can to eliminate
decadent elements in the country.
</P>
<P>
The excessive establishment of luxury nightclubs and night
spots that show videos will be curbed, and an appropriate ratio
will be set for the number of imported and domestic programs made
available in China, according to the ministry plan.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to basically wipe out the country's influx
of pornography and protect intellectual property rights by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ministry urges that the fight against pornographic and
illegal publications be continued, and that vulgar performances
and copies of artistic works should be prohibited.
</P>
<P>
"The cultural market can never be a hotbed for decadent
ideology and culture," said Meng Xiaosi, director of the cultural
market bureau of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bureau drafted 26 laws and regulations last
year, and some of them will be approved and enacted this year for
better management of the sector.
</P>
<P>
One of the ministry's greatest achievements was the closing of
more than 20 underground CD production lines in a series of raids
conducted jointly by the Press and Publications Administration and
the police.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fernandez Enters Australian Open Semi-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Mary Joe Fernandez of the
United States benefited from her opponents retirement and booked a
berth in the semi-final of the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez, the 14th-seeded player at this year's Australian
Open, was leading 7-5, 4-0 over Dominique van Roost of Belgium
when van Roost was forced to retire with a back injury.
</P>
<P>
Van Roost had acted as a giant-killer at the championships as
she beat second-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain in the
third round and 15th-seeded Chanda Rubin of the United States in
the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez had twice entered the finals of the Australian Open
in 1992 and 1994 respectively. 
</P>
