<HEADLINE> Space Firm Sets New Sights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China Aerospace Corp (CASC)
plans to intensify its co-operation with the world market as the
new century approaches, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
CASC, a State-owned corporation, plans to expand its
international business and hopes to become one of the world's top
companies by the end of the century, said Luo Ge, deputy director
of the corporation's Department of International Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
CASC will emphasize satellite technology and related products,
commercial launching services, and civilian mechanical and
electronic products geared toward the international market.
</P>
<P>
The corporation also plans to co-operate with large
international firms with the aim of setting up transnationals, Luo
said. The transnationals are expected to put CASC's production,
supply and sales on an international track.
</P>
<P>
"Entering the world market will promote the development of
China's space industry," Luo said.
</P>
<P>
China's President Jiang Zemin pledged at the 47th conference of
the International Astronautical Federation that China considers
the space sector to be a key priority.
</P>
<P>
Co-operation in commercial launchings, and in the space and
civilian industries, is expected to be carried out with firms
including: Hughes, Space Systems/Loral, TRW and Lockheed Martin of
the United States; SPAR of Canada; Alenia of Italy; and
Aerospatiale, Alcatel Espace and Sexton of France.  
</P>
</TEXT>
