<HEADLINE> Beijing Fights Firecrackers, Smoking in Public Places </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- With China's traditional Spring
Festival just around the corner, Beijing has stepped up its fight
against the selling and dealing of firecrackers, which have been
banned in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
And checks against violations of the smoking ban in public
places have also been carried out in the capital city, the Beijing
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ban on fireworks was enacted on December 1, 1993, and one
on smoking in public places went into effect on May 15, 1996. Both
are designed to reduce the number of fires, injuries and health
hazards, and "cultivate a civilized way of life."
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the local police have successfully
investigated eight violations of the fireworks ban since the
beginning of 1997, charging 11 offenders and confiscating 600,000
firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
Over 800,000 primary and middle school students were recently
mobilized by the municipal fireworks-ban office and youth league
to form a "Beijing Young Fire Brigade," which is expected to help
oversee the fireworks ban and fire control measures in the city,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal hygiene campaign committee recently organized
law-enforcement personnel to review the smoking ban's
effectiveness in public places such as libraries, railway
stations, university classrooms and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
It was found that the smoking ban has helped to greatly curb
smoking in those places, as only a small number of offenders were
caught and fined, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
