<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Mt. Merapi Remains in "Alert" Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A high alert was in force
around Indonesia's Mount Merapi volcano on Tuesday, four days
after it erupted spewing deadly heat clouds and forcing the
evacuation of 15,000 people, a volcano observation station
official said.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,126 people living within the danger zone were still
staying in the barracks that had been set up to accommodate them,
Antara news agency today quoted Soeramto, an officer at the
Volcano Observation Station as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the peak of the mountain was covered in clouds so that
the mountain's activities could not be observed visually.
</P>
<P>
The sound of avalanches of magmatic lava was still heard, he
said, adding that he could not determine their direction and
distance because of the clouds.
</P>
<P>
Soeramto said no heat clouds were produced in the last two days
while the tremors so far were caused by lava avalanches.
</P>
<P>
Although no other kinds of tremor happened, people had been
asked to stay alert because the intensity or timing of the
mountain's activities were hard to predict, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968-meter-high Merapi, one of the world's most active
volcanoes erupted in 1994, claiming 69 lives and leaving 5,000
homeless.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
