<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imperial Yuanmingyuan Garden Reproduced in Zhuhai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The replica of the imperial
Garden, Yuanmingyuan, which was burned to the ground by British and
French allied forces over 100 years ago, is near completion in
Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
Built during the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties in the western suburbs of Beijing, Yuanmingyuan, also
known as "the Garden of ten thousand Gardens," was considered a
masterpiece of Chinese architecture.
</P>
<P>
The garden was destroyed in 1860, and its ruins are now a major
tourist attraction in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The reproduction work, which started in 1992, covers an area of
600,000 square meters in Zhuhai, which is adjacent to Macao and
Hong Kong. The almost-finished section is the first phase of the
work, valued at 250 million yuan (30.12 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The replica represents one sixth of the original garden,
containing a dozen gardens fashioned in the style common to
southern China. Over 100 buildings and 10,000 precious trees, are
dotted around a lake of 80,000 square meters in area.
</P>
<P>
There are also art exhibits depicting the way of life and
politics during the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Designed by Qinghua University, the replica features the
talents of more than 2,000 historians, architects and artists from
all over China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
