<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Growing Car Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Poland, one of the fastest
developing car markets in Europe, will have 20 million vehicles in
2010 compared with the present seven million, experts estimate.
</P>
<P>
Car sales in Poland last year were 374,000 units, ranking
eighth in Europe and overtaking those of Austria and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The sales increase, the highest in Europe, was 41 percent over
the previous year. The trend is expected to continue as the demand
for trucks from the more than 1.9 million medium and small
enterprises increases.
</P>
<P>
Attracted by Poland's rising market and its government's
favorable investment conditions, many western car companies have
recently arrived to invest in car manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Fiat, the Italian car giant, bought most of shares of a Polish
mini-car factory in 1992 and sold 150,000 cars last year,
accounting for 46 percent of the Polish market.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Volkswagen Automobile Corporation and the United
States General Motors Corporation also invested in Poland in 1992
and 1993 to manufacture cars there.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the South Korean Daewoo Company bought 60 percent of
shares in the Polish Lublin Automobile Works and established the
Poland-Daewoo Automobile Company. The Daewoo Company, which sold
97,000 cars in Poland last year, planned to increase its
investment to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Opel Plant in Germany and the Ford Motors Corporation set
up car plants in Poland in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0267 </DOCNO>
