<HEADLINE> Philippine Business News in Brief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The following is business news
in brief in the Philippines:
</P>
<P>
-- The Board of Directors of the Philippine Airlines Tuesday
approved a plan to raise the airline's capital by 10 billion pesos
(380 million U.S. dollars) to 20 billion pesos (760 million
dollars) to shore up its finances and ensure adequate support for
its refleeting program. The increased part will be paid in two
equal installments of five billion each: the first, on or before
March 31, and the second, on or before March 31 next year.
</P>
<P>
-- The Philippine government has been offered by the U.S.-based
Morgan Stanley Asia Limited to issue this year a sovereign debt
note with 100 years maturity with an indicative price of 275 basis
points above the U.S. Treasury Bills with the same maturity. This
is the first time that the Philippines was invited to tap the
international bond market with a 100-year issue since its return
less than four years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Total automotive sales in the Philippines reached 162,095
units last year, up by 26 percent over the year of 1995 and
exceeding the industry's self-imposed target of 15-20 percent.
According to the Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers of the Phils.
Inc., passenger cars accounted for 55 percent of the total sales
while commercial vehicles reached 73,118 units. Toyota Motor
Phils. Inc. topped the list with 41,801 units, followed by
Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Honda Cars Phils. Inc., Nissan Motor
Phils. Inc. and Columbian Autocar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
