<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said yesterday that
administering a country by law not only is a sign of civilization
and progress for a society, but also a powerful guarantee of
long-term stability.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark when he met with participants who attended
a conference on law today, which was sponsored by the China Law
Society.
</P>
<P>
He said that this is a basic policy of China, as Deng Xiaoping
advocated the development of socialist democracy and the
strengthening of the socialist legal system, beginning with the
3rd Plenum of the 11th Central Committee of the Chinese Communist
Party in 1978.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng said here yesterday Sino-Japanese relations
should be given greater care, and that the responsibilities for
difficulties in the bilateral relations that occurred last year
did not rest with the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining and developing friendly Sino-Japanese relations and
cooperation conform to the fundamental interests of the two
peoples, Li told Yoshio Sakuauchi, president of the Japanese
Association for the Promotion of International Trade. The
bilateral relations can follow a "normal and healthy track" as
long as the two sides abide by the principles that govern such
relations.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China has always placed importance on its relations with
Vanuatu and wants to move the "friendly, mutually-beneficial, and
cooperative" relations to the new height.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin made this remark during his meeting with
Vanuatu Prime Minister Rialuth Serge Vohor yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Jiang values Vohor's efforts in Vanuatu-Chinese
relations, adding that the prime minister has also made a positive
contribution to the friendship and cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
-- China's state news agency, Xinhua, released an article,
entitled "Misguidance In Vain", written by Wen Ming, today.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that recently some US news media have
published commentaries and reports that are obviously against the
wishes of the people of both China and the United States, and in a
sharp contrast to the two countries' improved relations.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that there are a number of columnists and
scholars in the US who have a deeply-rooted prejudice and
hostility toward China, which perseveres in the road of socialism,
and are extremely reluctant to resign themselves to the fact that
the "overall containment" policy against China has ended in
failure.
</P>
<P>
-- China sent scholars abroad for further study in the past 18
years and this has helped train a large group of professionals and
increased China's cooperation with other countries in science and
technology, education, culture, economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
A national conference on returned scholars opened here
yesterday said that approximately 270,000 Chinese went abroad for
advanced training over the past 18 years. Over 120,000 of them
were sponsored by the government or their work units, with the
remainder self-supporting. Some 90,000 of these people have
completed their overseas study and returned.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China Aerospace Corp (CASC) plans to intensify its
cooperation with the world market as the new century approaches.
The state-owned corporation is to expand its international
business and hopes to become one of the world's top companies by
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
It would emphasize satellite technology and related products,
commercial launching services, and civilian mechanical and
electronic products geared toward the international market.
</P>
<P>
-- Hong Kong's existing laws will continue to be reviewed and
those contradictory to the Basic Law for Hong Kong will be
abolished, said Foreign Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang yesterday
at a routine press conference. 
</P>
