<HEADLINE> Central American, Caribbean Deputy Labor Ministers Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Deputy labor ministers from
Central America and the Caribbean began a two-day meeting today in
Panama to examine the participation of their countries in the Free
Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
The meeting will serve to "make an inventory on the needs" of
each country concerning correct inspection and labor relations,
said government spokesman Aixa de Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
The bases upon which the Labor Ministries of the region will be
modernized, its entry to the FTAA and gaining access to the World
Trade Organization, will be emphasized at the forum, declared
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
Deputy labor ministers from Belize, Dominica, Guatemala,
Honduras, Costa Rica, El Salvador and Nicaragua attended the
meeting which was inaugurated by Panamanian Labor Minister
Mitchell Doens.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by the U.S. ambassador to Panama,
William Hughes, as well as representatives from the International
Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of 34 countries from the American continent
pledged at the 1994 hemispherical summit to establish the FTAA by
the year 2005. 
