<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spark Program Means Great Changes for South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of farmers in south
China have better lives thanks to a program that started a decade
ago to develop the countryside by means of advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 4.9 billion yuan has been put into the
"Spark Program" in China's Guangdong Province, and had resulted in
29 billion yuan of added value.
</P>
<P>
Under the program 1,728 projects have been launched in the
province, 167 of which produced an annual output value of over ten
million yuan each, 29 major industries have taken shape, and more
than 400,000 farmers have received technical training.
</P>
<P>
A number of hi-tech development areas have been established in
the province, and the province has also set up the first national
Spark Program service center.
</P>
<P>
The development of township enterprises is one of the program's
targets. The province is now the country's largest poultry
production base, producing 800 million chickens, ducks, and geese
annually.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 technicians are involved in the program, 60
percent of whose projects are in mountainous areas, which are
rather less developed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
