<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Name of Poets, Historian Misused </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Poet Chen Mingyuan and the
Publishing House of China Federation of Literary and Art Circles
were said to have infringed upon the the name rights of the famous
Chinese poet and historian Guo Moruo, the China Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The case involves a book, "New Tide," published by the
publishing house in 1992 and with Chen Mingyuan and Guo Moruo
listed as co-authors.
</P>
<P>
In the book, Guo's 108 sonnets were rewritten into modern poems
by Chen.
</P>
<P>
Guo Moruo, a famous poet, historian and former head of the
Chinese academy of Sciences, was said to have not given permission
for Chen Mingyuan to publish books using his name, Guo's daughter
Guo Pingping said.
</P>
<P>
Guo died in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Chen Mingyuan could not offer evidence that he had Guo's
permission to use his name. He admitted he used Guo's name without
permission from his heir, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen argued in court that he worked with Guo for many
years on the book, which should be a joint effort of both of them.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Haidian People's Court ruled Chen had infringed
upon Guo's name rights by having his name printed as one of the
two authors of the book without permission of Guo's heir.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Chen could not give any evidence justifying the
use of Guo's name. The verdict also ruled that Chen used Guo's
poems without the permission of Guo's heir, and thus infringed on
her right to use Guo's works and to be paid for this.
</P>
<P>
The judgment rule that Chen and the publishing house should
apologize in national newspapers to Guo's daughter, compensate her
for her economic loss and cover all the lawsuit fees, the Daily
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
