<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Suggests 6-Month Renew of Force in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan recommended today that the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) be extended for another period of six months,
until 31 July 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, the secretary-general
noted that while the level of hostilities was somewhat lower than
that in the past, the situation in southern Lebanon continued to
be tense and volatile.
</P>
<P>
Israel maintained its occupation of parts of the area, while
Lebanese groups continued their attacks against the occupying
forces, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But it stressed that although the UNIFIL continued to be
prevented from implementing its mandate, which is to monitor the
withdrawal of Israeli troops, its contribution to stability and
the protection it was able to afford the population of the area
remained important.
</P>
<P>
In suggesting that the mandate renew for the 4,505-member force
established in 1978, the secretary-general also called upon member
states to pay their contributions.
</P>
<P>
"I must again draw attention to the serious shortfall in the
funding of the force," said the U.N. chief. "At present, unpaid
assessments amount to some 177 million U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
He said this money represented money owed to the member states
contributing the troops that make up the force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Set More New Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip shares on Wall
Street led stocks to more new highs today.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 40.03 points to
6,883.90, its fourth straight record finish and 10th in 12
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with the volume jumping to 571.26
million shares from 444.39 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 6.05 to 782.75; the
NYSE's composite index rose 2.26 to 411.57; the Nasdaq composite
index rose 11.32 to 1,375.60; and the Russell 2000 list of smaller
companies rose 0.98 to 370.33. All four measures set new highs.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.00 to
589.94.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the Dow's gain came from Boeing, which soared
on late Monday's news the company is halting plans to develop
larger 747 jets because there isn't enough demand to risk spending
up to 7 billion U.S. dollars on the project.
</P>
<P>
Technology shares also moved higher after a stream of
impressive profit reports and in advance of IBM's results.
</P>
<P>
Stocks started the day lower after interest rates rose in the
bond market amid worries about Federal Reserve chairman Allen
Greenspan's morning report to the Senate Budget Committee on the
state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell before Greenspan's speech, the yield on the
30-year Treasury bond jumped to nearly 6.89 percent from late
Friday's 6.83 percent. But as bonds recovered, the yield fell to
6.78 percent, boosting stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
