<HEADLINE> - Sudanese Vice-President Ends Visit to Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Vice-President
Al-Zubeir Mohammed Salih left here today after a two-day
discussion on the current military situation in eastern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He was seen off at the Damascus Airport by Syrian
Vice-President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed Syrian sources disclosed that during a meeting on
Monday, the Sudanese vice-president briefed Khaddam on what he
called external military intervention in Sudan aimed at
overthrowing the Sudanese government and undermining its unity
and the Arab nature of the country.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Syrian vice-president reiterated that his
country supports the territorial integrity of Sudan and unity of
its people, and opposes any foreign interference in Sudan's
internal affairs, on the grounds that Sudan's security is part and
parcel of the Arab security.
</P>
<P>
The visit by the Sudanese vice-president to Syria came within
the framework of several tours undertaken by Sudanese emissaries
dispatched by President Oman Hassan Ahmed al-Bashir to a number
of Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the tours is to brief the Arab leaders and
governments on the latest developments of the military situation
in Sudan, and seek Arab assistance in repelling what the
emissaries have described as Eritrean-Ethiopian aggression against
Sudan's territory and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government army has recently repelled an attack
in eastern Sudan. The offensive reportedly launched from Ethiopia
and Eritrea was under the command of southern Sudanese rebel
leader John Garang.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has accused Eritrea and Ethiopia of supporting and
fighting along with the Sudanese opposition, a charge rejected by
both countries. However the Sudanese opposition has denied any
external interference in the military maneuver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
