<HEADLINE> Parties of Cypriot Communities Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A Greek Cypriot party and a
Turkish Cypriot party today called for measures to defuse tension
in the divided Cyprus and a solution to the protracted Cyprus
problem through dialog.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Greek Cypriot United Democrats Party, a
small party which has seats in the Cypriot parliament, and Turkish
Cypriot leftist Republican Turkish Party from northern Cyprus had
a meeting here today to discuss the Cyprus problem and its recent
developments.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive coup seeking union with Greece. The Turkish Cypriots in
the north then declared an independent "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus", which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The tension has escalated recently on the island since the
Greek Cypriot government decided to buy Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missiles with a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued after the meeting said the two parties
voiced concern over the increase of tension on the island and an
"increase in chauvinistic tendencies."
</P>
<P>
It said "a solution to the Cyprus problem should be based on
political procedures and not military confrontation," and noted
that if the present situation continues there will be serious
consequences for both communities.
</P>
<P>
The two parties believe a dialog should begin soon, under the
auspices of the United Nations in order to reach a bicommunal,
bizonal solution to the Cyprus problem, as outlined in
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They also supported meetings between Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot political parties, noting these will help restore
confidence between the two communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
