<HEADLINE> Turkish Warships to Visit Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish navy ships will call
on ports of northern Cyprus Friday to show Turkey's unity with
Turkish Cypriots in confronting alleged military threats from
the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan made the announcement
here today after he got the information from Chief of General
Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces Ismail Hakki Karadayi.
</P>
<P>
However, it is unknown how many and what kind of Turkish
warships will visit the ports of northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Karadayi paid a two-day visit to northern Cyprus from January
13 to 14 to show Turkey's determination to block the deployment
of Russian-made S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that Turkey and northern Cyprus were tied to each
other in every way and the Turkish government would never
tolerate any threat to the security and rights of Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Welfare Party parliamentary group today, Erbakan
said that Turkey would abandon its long-standing passive stance
on the Cyprus issue and do what it can to assist northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
As for the Cypriot government's decision to purchase
anti-aircraft missiles, Erbakan reiterated that the Turkish
government would never allow the 150-kilometer-range missiles to
be deployed on the island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey did not care about how long the deployment
of the missiles would be delayed, adding it would make no
difference if the Cyprus government refused to give up the
arms program.
</P>
<P>
"If it is not declared within a certain time that the
missiles will not be coming, we will definitely not hesitate
to take the necessary steps," Erbakan warned.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cyprus has remained tense since the Cypriot
government contracted to buy S-300 missiles worth of 400
millions from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller
has warned that Turkey would not hesitate to hit these offensive
weapons if the Cypriot government goes ahead with the missile deal.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains divided since 1974 when Turkey occupied the
northern third of the strategic Mediterranean island in the wake
of an abortive coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 35,000 Turkish troops are stationed on the
island to protect the Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
