<HEADLINE> Chrysler Reports Record 1996 Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Chrysler Corporation, the
third largest auto maker of the U.S., today announced that both
its 1996 pretax earnings and vehicles sales hit their highest
points ever.
</P>
<P>
The company reported its pretax earnings reached 6.092 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase of 2.643 billion U.S. dollars represented 77
percent more than the 1995 pretax earnings of 3.449 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Net earnings as a percent of total revenues increased to 5.7
percent in 1996, compared to 3.8 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler's worldwide factory vehicle shipments in 1996 were
2,958,800 compared with 2,673,539 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company attributed the marked improvement to its strong
product line which turned out a wider range of models to the
market needs.
</P>
<P>
A company spokesman said that 1996 was the strongest year in
U.S. retail sales in the company's history. Chrysler finished
1996 with U.S. retail vehicle sales of 2,450,826, breaking the
1988 calendar-year record of 2,208,057. Its combined U.S. and
Canadian retail market share increased by 1.4 percentage points to
16.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Its combined U.S. and Canadian retail (including fleet) vehicle
sales in 1996 were 919,414 cars and 1,770,926 trucks and minivans,
compared with 883,769 cars and 1,505,696 trucks and minivans in
1995.
</P>
<P>
International retail sales grew to 222,035 units for 1996, a
19.4 percent increase over 185,934 units in 1995. Chrysler sold
102,139 units in Europe in 1996, an increase of 20.8 percent over
84,585 units in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
