<HEADLINE> US House Votes Reprimand, 300,000 Dlr Penalty for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States House of
Representatives today voted to give Speaker Newt Gingrich formal
reprimand and a penalty of 300,000 U.S. dollars for admitted
ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
The House voted 395-28 to punish Gingrich, the first House
speaker formally punished by vote of his colleagues for misconduct
in office in the country.
</P>
<P>
"No one is above the rules," Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.,
chairwoman of the ethics committee, said as the debate unfolded.
"Representative Gingrich failed to exercise the discipline and
caution of his office and so is subject to penalty today."
</P>
<P>
Gingrich was not present in the House chamber when his case was
brought before his peers.
</P>
<P>
The punishment permits Gingrich to hold his powerful post. The
House re-elected him its speaker two weeks ago despite of the
ethics case. But Gingrich apologized for his misconduct.
</P>
<P>
"To the degree I was too brash, too self-confident or too
pushy, I apologize," Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich agreed in advance to the punishment and the ethics
committee rubber-stamped it late Friday. On December 21, he said
he failed to seek proper legal advice on using tax-exempt projects
to meet political goals. He acknowledged that "in my name and over
my signature" inaccurate statements had been submitted to the
ethics committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
