<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Premier Promises Cooperation with UN Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb Premier Gojko
Klickovic said today that his government was ready to cooperate
with the U.N. war crimes tribunal, but he stressed that the Serbs
must be treated equally with the other parties in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in the Serb capital of Pale after meeting
with the prosecutor of the Hague-based War Crimes Tribunal for
Former Yugoslavia, Louise Arbour, who was paying a visit to Pale
at the invitation of the Serb government because the Serb
authorities believed that unfair treatment was accorded to the
Serb side in the investigation of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
Klickovic said that in the cases involving the Serbs, decisions
were made quickly, whereas in the case of the other parties
involved in war crimes, the establishment of facts was proceeding
slowly and with difficulty.
</P>
<P>
The international war crimes tribunal has listed 75 war
criminals in the former Yugoslavia, of whom more than 50 are
Serbs, including former Serb President Radovan Karadzic and Serb
Army Commander Ratko Mladic. So far only one Croat soldier serving
in the Bosnian Serb army has been sentenced to 10-year
imprisonment and seven suspects are under custody in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
According to ther Tanjug news agency, the Serb premier said the
Serb government had worked out its own position as regards the
court's indictments of Karadzic and Mladic. Eleven documents had
been drawn up to show that most allegations presented by the court
were unfounded, he added.
</P>
<P>
So far the Serb authorities have refused to hand out Karadzic
and Mladic, the most wanted men by the war crimes tribunal despite
strong pressure from the court and the West.
</P>
<P>
Arbour told reporters in Pale that the court would not be able
to deal with all crimes committed in these lands in the course of
the war and that some people would be answerable only to their
conscience and to God for what they had done during the
43-month-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
All that was expected of the court and all that it could do was
to investigate certain crimes, establish the facts of the case and
prosecute individuals responsible for those crimes, Arbour said.
</P>
<P>
Allegations had to be proven publicly, beyond any doubt, in a
fair trial, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970122.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
