<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Chairman Warns of Renewed Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
Chairman Alan Greenspan said today that the good news on inflation
may be ending as low unemployment leads to rising wage demands in
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In his testimony to the Senate Budget Committee of the U.S.
Congress, Greenspan said that "the overall performance of the U.S.
economy has continued to surpass most forecasters' expectations."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the U.S. Fed is on heightened alert that at
some point that the low unemployment rate will spawn inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan emphasized that inflationary pressures in the U.S.
have not yet become evident even though the current recovery is
now the third longest in history and has driven unemployment down
to 5.3 percent, near a seven-year low.
</P>
<P>
"The question is, of course, where do we go from here?" he
said. "Can we continue to achieve significant gains in real
activity while avoiding inflationary excesses?"
</P>
<P>
He said that widespread job insecurities have kept wage
pressures constrained even though labor markets are tight, but
"the trade-off of subdued wage growth for job security has to come
to an end" at some point in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that there has been a recent pickup in some measures of
wages that "suggests that the transition may already be running
its course."
</P>
<P>
Economists viewed Greenspan's comments today as a clear signal
that the U.S. Fed's next move will be to tighten monetary policy.
Some economists have begun to believe that the U.S. Fed will soon
start raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that the U.S. economic growth, as measured
by the gross domestic product, was expanding at an annual rate of
3.5 percent to 4 percent in the final three months of last year,
up from a 2.1 percent rate in the third quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
